{"title_page": "Hal Clements", "text_new": "'''Hal Clements''' was an actor and director of [[silent film]]s in the U.S. He starred in dozens of [[silent film]]s. He married writer [[Olga Printzlau]].\n\nClements was part of [[Kalem Company|Kalem's]] Jacksonville film crew.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=UtFlWOHc7nYC&pg=PA241&dq=%22hal+clements%22&hl=en&sa=X&ved=0ahUKEwj4qPC4s_DoAhVRiOAKHcsgBN4Q6AEIYzAI#v=onepage&q=%22hal+clements%22&f=false|title=The Sounds of Early Cinema|first1=Richard|last1=Abel|first2=Rick R.|last2=Altman|date=October 3, 2001|publisher=Indiana University Press|via=Google Books}}</ref> In 1914, he directed and managed the studio's comedy unit in [[Santa Monica]] featuring [[Ruth Roland]] and [[John Brennan (actor)]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=UEs_AAAAYAAJ&pg=PA671&dq=%22hal+clements%22&hl=en&sa=X&ved=2ahUKEwjnxaWRtfDoAhWmVN8KHShWADo4ChDoATADegQIARAW#v=onepage&q=%22hal+clements%22&f=false|title=The Moving Picture World|date=April 17, 1914|publisher=Chalmers Publishing Company|via=Google Books}}</ref> He portrayed General John Pershing in a [[Thomas H. Ince|Thomas Ince]] film.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=ihpdK6a2AfAC&pg=PA143&dq=%22hal+clements%22&hl=en&sa=X&ved=0ahUKEwj4qPC4s_DoAhVRiOAKHcsgBN4Q6AEIWzAH#v=onepage&q=%22hal+clements%22&f=false|title=Thomas Ince: Hollywood's Independent Pioneer|first=Brian|last=Taves|date=April 17, 2012|publisher=University Press of Kentucky|via=Google Books}}</ref> In 1916 he was managing director of the new Gate City Feature Film Company.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=1qgbAQAAMAAJ&pg=PA958&lpg=PA958&dq=%22hal+clements%22+obituary+film&source=bl&ots=0Kr1ZJPW-j&sig=ACfU3U0qjiTcOfjJb_0zk5Cg7kzYz9CtZg&hl=en&sa=X&ved=2ahUKEwjwqeqwuPDoAhXyQ98KHZFBBoYQ6AEwAXoECAgQAQ#v=onepage&q=%22hal+clements%22+obituary+film&f=false|title=The Moving Picture World|date=April 17, 1916|publisher=World Photographic Publishing Company|via=Google Books}}</ref>\n\n==Filmography==\n* ''[[Uncle Tom's Cabin (1913 film)]]''\n* ''[[The Grim Toll of War]]'' (1913)<ref name=wire>{{Cite web|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=um5ZAAAAMAAJ&q=%22hal+clements%22&dq=%22hal+clements%22&hl=en&sa=X&ved=2ahUKEwidpbTftvDoAhWsiOAKHTuBArE4FBDoATACegQIARAO|title=Those fabulous serial heroines: their lives and films|first=Buck|last=Rainey|date=April 17, 1990|publisher=Scarecrow Press|via=pages.101, 271, 294}}</ref>\n* ''[[O'Brien Finds a Way]]'' (1914)\n* ''[[Armstrong's Wife]]'' (1915)\n* ''[[Out of the Darkness (1915 film)]]''\n* ''[[The Unknown (1915 drama film)]]''\n* ''[[The Secret Sin]]'' (1915)\n* ''[[The Immigrant (1915 film)]]''\n* ''[[The Girl Telegrapher's Nerve]]'' (1916)\n* ''[[Miss Jackie of the Army]]'' (1917)<ref>{{Cite book | url=https://books.google.com/?id=3Se6CwAAQBAJ&pg=PA150&lpg=PA150&dq=%22hal+clements%22#v=onepage |title = World War I on Film: English Language Releases through 2014|isbn = 9781476620633|last1 = Edwards|first1 = Paul M.|date = 11 March 2016}}</ref>\n* ''[[An American Live Wire]]'' (1918)<ref name=wire/>\n* ''[[Other Men's Wives]]'' (1919)\n* ''[[An Innocent Adventuress]]'' (1919)\n* ''[[The Siege of Petersburg]]''\n* ''[[The Sacrifice at the Spillway]]''<ref>{{Cite web | url=https://books.google.com/?id=5jAXAQAAMAAJ&pg=RA5-PA144&lpg=RA5-PA144&dq=%22hal+clements%22#v=onepage |title = Motion Picture|year = 1913}}</ref>\n* ''The Man Who Could Not Lose'', a Biograph film, as Jack Carter<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=JBIXAQAAMAAJ&pg=PA146&dq=%22hal+clements%22&hl=en&sa=X&ved=0ahUKEwj4qPC4s_DoAhVRiOAKHcsgBN4Q6AEITDAF#v=onepage&q=%22hal+clements%22&f=false|title=Motion Picture|date=April 17, 1915|publisher=Macfadden-Bartell.|via=Google Books}}</ref>\n* ''[[Seventeen (1940 film)]]''\n* ''[[Wichita (1955 film)|Wichita]]'' (1955)<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=tSX8EUOlqT0C&pg=PA308&dq=%22hal+clements%22&hl=en&sa=X&ved=0ahUKEwj4qPC4s_DoAhVRiOAKHcsgBN4Q6AEIUzAG#v=onepage&q=%22hal+clements%22&f=false|title=Jacques Tourneur: The Cinema of Nightfall|first=Chris|last=Fujiwara|date=May 7, 2015|publisher=McFarland|via=Google Books}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n*[https://www.imdb.com/name/nm0166226/ Hal Clements] on [[IMDb]]\n\n{{authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Clements, Hal}}\n[[Category:American silent film actors]]\n[[Category:American film directors]]\n[[Category:Year of birth missing]]\n[[Category:Year of death missing]]\n\n\n{{US-film-actor-stub}}\n{{US-film-director-stub}}\n", "text_old": "'''Hal Clements''' was an actor and director of [[silent film]]s in the U.S. He starred in dozens of [[silent film]]s. He married writer [[Olga Printzlau]].\n\nClements was part of [[Kalem Company|Kalem's]] Jacksonville film crew.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=UtFlWOHc7nYC&pg=PA241&dq=%22hal+clements%22&hl=en&sa=X&ved=0ahUKEwj4qPC4s_DoAhVRiOAKHcsgBN4Q6AEIYzAI#v=onepage&q=%22hal+clements%22&f=false|title=The Sounds of Early Cinema|first1=Richard|last1=Abel|first2=Rick R.|last2=Altman|date=October 3, 2001|publisher=Indiana University Press|via=Google Books}}</ref> In 1914, he directed and managed the studio's comedy unit in [[Santa Monica]] featuring [[Ruth Roland]] and [[John Brennan (actor)]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=UEs_AAAAYAAJ&pg=PA671&dq=%22hal+clements%22&hl=en&sa=X&ved=2ahUKEwjnxaWRtfDoAhWmVN8KHShWADo4ChDoATADegQIARAW#v=onepage&q=%22hal+clements%22&f=false|title=The Moving Picture World|date=April 17, 1914|publisher=Chalmers Publishing Company|via=Google Books}}</ref> He portrayed General John Pershing in a [[Thomas H. Ince|Thomas Ince]] film.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=ihpdK6a2AfAC&pg=PA143&dq=%22hal+clements%22&hl=en&sa=X&ved=0ahUKEwj4qPC4s_DoAhVRiOAKHcsgBN4Q6AEIWzAH#v=onepage&q=%22hal+clements%22&f=false|title=Thomas Ince: Hollywood's Independent Pioneer|first=Brian|last=Taves|date=April 17, 2012|publisher=University Press of Kentucky|via=Google Books}}</ref> In 1916 he was managing director of the new Gate City Feature Film Company.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=1qgbAQAAMAAJ&pg=PA958&lpg=PA958&dq=%22hal+clements%22+obituary+film&source=bl&ots=0Kr1ZJPW-j&sig=ACfU3U0qjiTcOfjJb_0zk5Cg7kzYz9CtZg&hl=en&sa=X&ved=2ahUKEwjwqeqwuPDoAhXyQ98KHZFBBoYQ6AEwAXoECAgQAQ#v=onepage&q=%22hal+clements%22+obituary+film&f=false|title=The Moving Picture World|date=April 17, 1916|publisher=World Photographic Publishing Company|via=Google Books}}</ref>\n\n==Filmography==\n* ''[[Uncle Tom's Cabin (1913 film)]]''\n* ''[[The Grim Toll of War]]'' (1913)<ref name=wire>{{Cite web|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=um5ZAAAAMAAJ&q=%22hal+clements%22&dq=%22hal+clements%22&hl=en&sa=X&ved=2ahUKEwidpbTftvDoAhWsiOAKHTuBArE4FBDoATACegQIARAO|title=Those fabulous serial heroines: their lives and films|first=Buck|last=Rainey|date=April 17, 1990|publisher=Scarecrow Press|via=pages.101, 271, 294}}</ref>\n* ''[[O'Brien Finds a Way]]'' (1914)\n* ''[[Armstrong's Wife]]'' (1915)\n* ''[[Out of the Darkness (1915 film)]]''\n* ''[[The Unknown (1915 drama film)]]''\n* ''[[The Secret Sin]]'' (1915)\n* ''[[The Immigrant (1915 film)]]''\n* ''[[The Girl Telegrapher's Nerve]]'' (1916)\n* ''[[Miss Jackie of the Army]]'' (1917)<ref>{{Cite book | url=https://books.google.com/?id=3Se6CwAAQBAJ&pg=PA150&lpg=PA150&dq=%22hal+clements%22#v=onepage |title = World War I on Film: English Language Releases through 2014|isbn = 9781476620633|last1 = Edwards|first1 = Paul M.|date = 11 March 2016}}</ref>\n* ''[[An American Live Wire]]'' (1918)<ref name=wire/>\n* ''[[Other Men's Wives]]'' (1919)\n* ''[[An Innocent Adventuress]]'' (1919)\n* ''[[The Siege of Petersburg]]''\n* ''[[The Sacrifice at the Spillway]]''<ref>{{Cite web | url=https://books.google.com/?id=5jAXAQAAMAAJ&pg=RA5-PA144&lpg=RA5-PA144&dq=%22hal+clements%22#v=onepage |title = Motion Picture|year = 1913}}</ref>\n* ''The Man Who Could Not Lose'', a Biograph film, as Jack Carter<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=JBIXAQAAMAAJ&pg=PA146&dq=%22hal+clements%22&hl=en&sa=X&ved=0ahUKEwj4qPC4s_DoAhVRiOAKHcsgBN4Q6AEITDAF#v=onepage&q=%22hal+clements%22&f=false|title=Motion Picture|date=April 17, 1915|publisher=Macfadden-Bartell.|via=Google Books}}</ref>\n* ''[[Seventeen (1940 film)]]''\n* ''[[Wichita (1955 film)|Wichita]]'' (1955)<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=tSX8EUOlqT0C&pg=PA308&dq=%22hal+clements%22&hl=en&sa=X&ved=0ahUKEwj4qPC4s_DoAhVRiOAKHcsgBN4Q6AEIUzAG#v=onepage&q=%22hal+clements%22&f=false|title=Jacques Tourneur: The Cinema of Nightfall|first=Chris|last=Fujiwara|date=May 7, 2015|publisher=McFarland|via=Google Books}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n*[https://www.imdb.com/name/nm0166226/ Hal Clements] on [[IMDB]]\n\n{{authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Clements, Hal}}\n[[Category:American silent film actors]]\n[[Category:American film directors]]\n[[Category:Year of birth missing]]\n[[Category:Year of death missing]]\n\n\n{{US-film-actor-stub}}\n{{US-film-director-stub}}\n", "name_user": "Wbm1058", "label": "safe", "comment": "IMDb(viaWP:JWB)", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Hal_Clements"}
{"title_page": "Gajender Singh Bisht", "text_new": "{{Use dmy dates|date=July 2017}}\n{{Use Indian English|date=July 2017}}\n{{Infobox military person\n| honorific_prefix = [[Havildar]]\n| name          = Gajender Singh Bisht\n| honorific_suffix = [[Ashok Chakra Award|AC]]\n| image         = Havildar Gajender Singh.jpg\n| image_size    = 250 px\n| birth_date    = \n| death_date    = {{Death date|df=yes|2008|11|28|}}\n| birth_place   = [[Dehradun]], [[Uttarakhand]]\n| death_place   = [[Mumbai]], [[Maharashtra]]\n| allegiance    = {{flagicon|India}} [[India]]\n| branch        = [[File:Flag of Indian Army.svg|24px]] [[Indian Army]]\n| serviceyears  = 1990&ndash;2008\n| rank          = [[File:Indian Army Havildar.gif|50px]][[Havildar]]\n| unit          = [[51 Special Action Group|51 SAG, NSG]]<br/><!-- Commented out: [[File:ParasIndia.JPG|40px]] -->[[Parachute Regiment (India)|Parachute Regiment]]\n| battles       = [[2008 Mumbai attacks|Operation Black Tornado]]\n| awards        = [[File:Ashoka Chakra ribbon.svg|34px]] [[Ashoka Chakra Award|Ashoka Chakra]]\n}}\n'''Gajender Singh Bisht''' (1972 \u2013 28 November 2008) was an [[National Security Guards|NSG]] commando and [[Havildar]] ([[Sergeant]]) who was martyred during the [[2008 Mumbai attacks]]. His act of bravery was honoured with the [[Ashoka Chakra Award|Ashoka Chakra award]] by the [[President (government title)|President]] of [[India]] on [[26&nbsp;January]] 2009, India's [[Republic Day (India)|Republic Day]].<ref name=\"ashoka\">{{cite news|url=http://ibnlive.in.com/news/11-security-personnel-to-get-ashok-chakra/83597-3.html|title=11 security personnel to get Ashok Chakra|accessdate=2009-01-25}}</ref>\n\n==Childhood==\nHailing from Ganeshpur in [[Dehradun]], [[Uttarakhand]], young Gajender Singh studied at the Janata Inter College in Naya Gaon. He was remembered by his teachers as a disciplined student who participated in every event organised in the school, sports or cultural activities. He had a particular interest in boxing.<ref name=\"aaa\">{{cite web|url=http://www.indianexpress.com/news/he-had-always-wanted-to-die-a-heros-death/392346/|title=\u2018He had always wanted to die a hero\u2019s death\u2019|first=Rajeev |last=khanna|accessdate=2009-01-27}}</ref>\n\n==Operation Black Tornado==\n\nGajender Singh was a member of the [[National Security Guard]]\u2019s [[51 Special Action Group]]. Gajender Singh was part of the team of NSG commandos who were [[fast-roping|fast-roped]] on the roof of Nariman House in an operation to neutralize the terrorists inside who were holding at least six hostages.\n\nAccording to Jyoti Krishna Dutt, Director General of the NSG, Singh was leading one of the teams that entered the building. The team came under intense fire from the terrorists and returned fire, while trying to dominate the situation. The terrorists also hurled a few grenades at the commandos. At this point, Singh had the option of retreating with his team. However, he realized that they had to seize this opportunity to dominate and continued moving ahead. He didn't turn his back to the militants and created a way for the other commandos despite a grenade thrown at him. Despite sustaining multiple bullet injuries while doing so, he moved forward and ultimately succumbed to his injuries, making the supreme sacrifice. This selfless and brave gesture of his ensured that his team secured a dominating position in the encounter.<ref name=\"HT\">{{cite web|url=http://www.hindustantimes.com/StoryPage/FullcoverageStoryPage.aspx?id=5a23e305-3ee7-483e-88c3-5aeea3ef1902Mumbaiunderattack_Special&MatchID1=4858&TeamID1=1&TeamID2=5&MatchType1=1&SeriesID1=1224&PrimaryID=4858&Headline=Tributes+paid+to+NSG+commando+Gajender+in+Delhi|title=Slain NSG commando paid tributes at special ceremony in Delhi|access-date=2009-01-27|url-status=dead|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20081210144958/http://www.hindustantimes.com/StoryPage/FullcoverageStoryPage.aspx?id=5a23e305-3ee7-483e-88c3-5aeea3ef1902Mumbaiunderattack_Special&MatchID1=4858&TeamID1=1&TeamID2=5&MatchType1=1&SeriesID1=1224&PrimaryID=4858&Headline=Tributes+paid+to+NSG+commando+Gajender+in+Delhi|archive-date=10 December 2008|df=dmy-all}}</ref>\n\n== Death ==\nWhile securing the [[Nariman House]] during [[2008 Mumbai attacks|Operation Black Tornado]], Singh, a member of the Parachute Regiment was fatally wounded while storming the Jewish center. According to army, his death was due to TV channels broadcasting the live operation, which gave away the surprise element and alerted terrorists.\n\n==Ashoka Chakra Award Citation==\n[[File:Smt. Vineeta Devi receiving Ashoka Chakra awarded to her husband Havildar Gajender Singh (Posthumous) from the President, Smt. Pratibha Devisingh Patil, during the 60th Republic Day Parade-2009, in New Delhi.jpg|right|thumb|Gajender Singh Bisht's wife receives the Ashok Chakra from president Pratibha Patil on 26 January 2009.]]\nThe official citation for the [[Ashoka Chakra Award]] reads:\n\n{{Quotation|<center>'''4073611 HAVILDAR GAJENDER SINGH PARACHUTE REGIMENT / 51 SPECIAL ACTION GROUP (POSTHUMOUS)'''</center>\n\nIn the night of 27th November 2008, Havildar Gajender Singh was leading his squad in the operation to rescue hostages from the terrorists at Nariman House, Mumbai.\n\nAfter clearing the top floor of the terrorists, he reached the place where the terrorists had taken position.  As he closed in, the terrorists hurled a grenade injuring him.  Undeterred, he kept firing and closing in on the terrorists by exposing himself to the hostile fire.  In the act, he injured one of the terrorists and forced the others to retreat inside a room.  He continued the encounter till he succumbed to his injuries.\n\nHavildar Gajender Singh displayed most conspicuous courage against grave odds and made the supreme sacrifice for the nation in combating the terrorists.<ref name=PIB>{{citation|url=http://pib.nic.in/newsite/erelease.aspx?relid=46980|accessdate=14 September 2014|date=25 January 2009|title=Ashoka Chakra awardees and their saga of gallantry |publisher=Press Information Bureau, Government of India}}</ref>}}\n\n==See also==\n* [[Hemant Karkare]]\n* [[Sandeep Unnikrishnan]]\n* [[Vijay Salaskar]]\n* [[Ashok Kamte]]\n* [[Tukaram Omble]]\n\n==References==\n<References/>\n\n{{Template:Ashoka Chakra award recipients}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Singh, Havaldar Gajender}}\n[[Category:2008 deaths]]\n[[Category:Deaths by firearm in India]]\n[[Category:Terrorism victims in India]]\n[[Category:Victims of the 2008 Mumbai attacks]]\n[[Category:Recipients of the Ashoka Chakra (military decoration)]]\n[[Category:1972 births]]\n[[Category:Military personnel from Dehradun]]\n[[Category:Ashoka Chakra]]\n", "text_old": "{{Use dmy dates|date=July 2017}}\n{{Use Indian English|date=July 2017}}\n{{Infobox military person\n| honorific_prefix = [[Havildar]]\n| name          = Gajender Singh Bisht\n| honorific_suffix = [[Ashok Chakra Award|AC]]\n| image         = Havildar Gajender Singh.jpg\n| image_size    = 250 px\n| birth_date    = \n| death_date    = {{Death date|df=yes|2008|11|28|}}\n| birth_place   = [[Dehradun]], [[Uttarakhand]]\n| death_place   = [[Mumbai]], [[Maharashtra]]\n| allegiance    = {{flagicon|India}} [[India]]\n| branch        = [[File:Flag of Indian Army.svg|24px]] [[Indian Army]]\n| serviceyears  = 1990&ndash;2008\n| rank          = [[File:Indian Army Havildar.gif|50px]][[Havildar]]\n| unit          = [[51 Special Action Group|51 SAG, NSG]]<br/><!-- Commented out: [[File:ParasIndia.JPG|40px]] -->[[Parachute Regiment (India)|Parachute Regiment]]\n| battles       = [[2008 Mumbai attacks|Operation Black Tornado]]\n| awards        = [[File:Ashoka Chakra ribbon.svg|34px]] [[Ashoka Chakra Award|Ashoka Chakra]]\n}}\n'''Gajender Singh Bisht''' (1972 \u2013 28 November 2008) was an [[National Security Guards|NSG]] commando and [[Havildar]] ([[Sergeant]]) who was martyred during the [[2008 Mumbai attacks]]. His act of bravery was honoured with the [[Ashoka Chakra Award|Ashoka Chakra award]] by the [[President]] of [[India]] on [[26&nbsp;January]] 2009, India's [[Republic Day (India)|Republic Day]].<ref name=\"ashoka\">{{cite news|url=http://ibnlive.in.com/news/11-security-personnel-to-get-ashok-chakra/83597-3.html|title=11 security personnel to get Ashok Chakra|accessdate=2009-01-25}}</ref>\n\n==Childhood==\nHailing from Ganeshpur in [[Dehradun]], [[Uttarakhand]], young Gajender Singh studied at the Janata Inter College in Naya Gaon. He was remembered by his teachers as a disciplined student who participated in every event organised in the school, sports or cultural activities. He had a particular interest in boxing.<ref name=\"aaa\">{{cite web|url=http://www.indianexpress.com/news/he-had-always-wanted-to-die-a-heros-death/392346/|title=\u2018He had always wanted to die a hero\u2019s death\u2019|first=Rajeev |last=khanna|accessdate=2009-01-27}}</ref>\n\n==Operation Black Tornado==\n\nGajender Singh was a member of the [[National Security Guard]]\u2019s [[51 Special Action Group]]. Gajender Singh was part of the team of NSG commandos who were [[fast-roping|fast-roped]] on the roof of Nariman House in an operation to neutralize the terrorists inside who were holding at least six hostages.\n\nAccording to Jyoti Krishna Dutt, Director General of the NSG, Singh was leading one of the teams that entered the building. The team came under intense fire from the terrorists and returned fire, while trying to dominate the situation. The terrorists also hurled a few grenades at the commandos. At this point, Singh had the option of retreating with his team. However, he realized that they had to seize this opportunity to dominate and continued moving ahead. He didn't turn his back to the militants and created a way for the other commandos despite a grenade thrown at him. Despite sustaining multiple bullet injuries while doing so, he moved forward and ultimately succumbed to his injuries, making the supreme sacrifice. This selfless and brave gesture of his ensured that his team secured a dominating position in the encounter.<ref name=\"HT\">{{cite web|url=http://www.hindustantimes.com/StoryPage/FullcoverageStoryPage.aspx?id=5a23e305-3ee7-483e-88c3-5aeea3ef1902Mumbaiunderattack_Special&MatchID1=4858&TeamID1=1&TeamID2=5&MatchType1=1&SeriesID1=1224&PrimaryID=4858&Headline=Tributes+paid+to+NSG+commando+Gajender+in+Delhi|title=Slain NSG commando paid tributes at special ceremony in Delhi|access-date=2009-01-27|url-status=dead|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20081210144958/http://www.hindustantimes.com/StoryPage/FullcoverageStoryPage.aspx?id=5a23e305-3ee7-483e-88c3-5aeea3ef1902Mumbaiunderattack_Special&MatchID1=4858&TeamID1=1&TeamID2=5&MatchType1=1&SeriesID1=1224&PrimaryID=4858&Headline=Tributes+paid+to+NSG+commando+Gajender+in+Delhi|archive-date=10 December 2008|df=dmy-all}}</ref>\n\n== Death ==\nWhile securing the [[Nariman House]] during [[2008 Mumbai attacks|Operation Black Tornado]], Singh, a member of the Parachute Regiment was fatally wounded while storming the Jewish center. According to army, his death was due to TV channels broadcasting the live operation, which gave away the surprise element and alerted terrorists.\n\n==Ashoka Chakra Award Citation==\n[[File:Smt. Vineeta Devi receiving Ashoka Chakra awarded to her husband Havildar Gajender Singh (Posthumous) from the President, Smt. Pratibha Devisingh Patil, during the 60th Republic Day Parade-2009, in New Delhi.jpg|right|thumb|Gajender Singh Bisht's wife receives the Ashok Chakra from president Pratibha Patil on 26 January 2009.]]\nThe official citation for the [[Ashoka Chakra Award]] reads:\n\n{{Quotation|<center>'''4073611 HAVILDAR GAJENDER SINGH PARACHUTE REGIMENT / 51 SPECIAL ACTION GROUP (POSTHUMOUS)'''</center>\n\nIn the night of 27th November 2008, Havildar Gajender Singh was leading his squad in the operation to rescue hostages from the terrorists at Nariman House, Mumbai.\n\nAfter clearing the top floor of the terrorists, he reached the place where the terrorists had taken position.  As he closed in, the terrorists hurled a grenade injuring him.  Undeterred, he kept firing and closing in on the terrorists by exposing himself to the hostile fire.  In the act, he injured one of the terrorists and forced the others to retreat inside a room.  He continued the encounter till he succumbed to his injuries.\n\nHavildar Gajender Singh displayed most conspicuous courage against grave odds and made the supreme sacrifice for the nation in combating the terrorists.<ref name=PIB>{{citation|url=http://pib.nic.in/newsite/erelease.aspx?relid=46980|accessdate=14 September 2014|date=25 January 2009|title=Ashoka Chakra awardees and their saga of gallantry |publisher=Press Information Bureau, Government of India}}</ref>}}\n\n==See also==\n* [[Hemant Karkare]]\n* [[Sandeep Unnikrishnan]]\n* [[Vijay Salaskar]]\n* [[Ashok Kamte]]\n* [[Tukaram Omble]]\n\n==References==\n<References/>\n\n{{Template:Ashoka Chakra award recipients}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Singh, Havaldar Gajender}}\n[[Category:2008 deaths]]\n[[Category:Deaths by firearm in India]]\n[[Category:Terrorism victims in India]]\n[[Category:Victims of the 2008 Mumbai attacks]]\n[[Category:Recipients of the Ashoka Chakra (military decoration)]]\n[[Category:1972 births]]\n[[Category:Military personnel from Dehradun]]\n[[Category:Ashoka Chakra]]\n", "name_user": "Rodw", "label": "safe", "comment": "Disambiguating links toPresident(link changed toPresident (government title)) usingDisamAssist.", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Gajender_Singh_Bisht"}
{"title_page": "Revolt (film)", "text_new": "{{Infobox film\n| name           = Revolt\n| image          = Revolt (film poster).jpg\n| alt            = \n| caption        = Theatrical release poster\n| director       = Joe Miale\n| producer       = {{Plainlist|\n* Rory Aitken\n* Nicolas Chartier\n* Zev Foreman\n* James Harris\n* Brian Kavanaugh-Jones\n* Ben Pugh\n}}\n| writer         = {{Plainlist|\n* Rowan Athale\n* Joe Miale\n}}\n| starring       = {{Plainlist|\n* [[Lee Pace]]\n* [[B\u00e9r\u00e9nice Marlohe]]}}\n| music          = [[Bear McCreary]]\n| cinematography = [[Karl Walter Lindenlaub]]\n| editing        = Evan Schiff, Vincent Tabaillon\n| distributor    = Albatros Film (Japan) (theatrical)\nThe Klockworx (Japan) (theatrical)\nDutch FilmWorks (DFW) (Netherlands) (Blu-ray and DVD)\nVideoland (Netherlands) (video) (VOD)\nShaw Organisation (Singapore) (theatrical)\nEagle Entertainment (Australia) (DVD)\nKoch Media (Germany) (Blu-ray and DVD)\nVertical Entertainment (USA) (all media)\nGEM Entertainment (multi-territory) (all media)\nFilm & TV House (multi-territory) (all media)\n| released       = {{Film date|2017|07|01|Japan}}\n| runtime        = 1h 27min<ref>{{cite web|title=REVOLT 2017|url=https://www.cinemaclock.com/movies/revolt-2017|website=[[CINEMACLOCK]]|publisher=cinemaclock.com|access-date=20 April 2020}}</ref>\n| country        = United States\n| language       = English\n| budget         = 4 million (estimated)\n| gross          = $15,430 (theatrical) $24,416  (total)<ref>{{cite web|title=REVOLT 2017|url=https://www.imdb.com/title/tt3722614/?ref_=ttexst_exst_tt\\|website=[[IMDb]]|publisher=imdb.com|access-date=20 April 2020}}</ref>\n| production companies = {{Plainlist|\n* [[Voltage Pictures]] (presents)\n* 42\n* Automatik\n* Tea Shop & Film Company (in association with)\n* MacDuff\n* POW Movie\n}}\n}}\n\n'''''Revolt''''' is a 2017 American [[science fiction]] film directed by Joe Miale.<ref>{{cite web|title=REVOLT 2017|url=https://www.rottentomatoes.com/m/revolt_2017/|website=[[Rotten Tomatoes]]|publisher=rottentomatoes.com|accessdate=7 January 2018}}</ref> It was written by Miale and Rowan Athale, staring [[Lee Pace]] and [[B\u00e9r\u00e9nice Marlohe]] as lead roles.<ref>{{cite web|title=Revolt|url=https://www.movieinsider.com/m15869/revolt|website=Movie Insider|publisher=movieinsider.com|accessdate=7 January 2018}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=Revolt 2017 film|url=http://www.metacritic.com/movie/revolt|website=[[Metacritic]]|publisher=metacritic.com|accessdate=7 January 2018}}</ref>\n\n==Plot==\n\nAn American Special Forces soldier ([[Lee Pace]]), serving in [[Kenya]], suffers [[Amnesia|memory loss]] after being knocked unconscious during a battle with [[Bipedalism|bipedal]] robotic machines. He later wakes up in a jail cell meeting Nadia ([[B\u00e9r\u00e9nice Marlohe]]), a French foreign aid doctor who tells him they were taken prisoner by a gang of thugs. She calls him \"Bo\" after seeing the letters on his torn name tag. Nadia explains to Bo that the world had been invaded by alien machines wiping out all the major cities and countries along with their respected military forces. After escaping the jail cell, Bo decides to make his way to a U.S. military base somewhere near [[Nairobi]]. Nadia tags along with Bo with little optimism. Bo only recalls fragments of what happened to him while discovering his ability to absorb, conduct, and discharge electricity. Bo and Nadia encounter a fatally wounded photo journalist ([[Jason Flemyng]]). The photo journalist passes on his camera to Bo telling him to follow the photos as a way to the U.S. military base. Along the way, Nadia is abducted by the alien machines forcing Bo to go on alone and injured. He finally makes it to the military base, only to find it in ruins. Collapsing from his wounds, Bo is eventually saved by a group of Nairobi resistance fighters who plan to detonate an EMP bomb near the alien's mother ship in order to bring it down and deactivate the machines. Bo finally recalls his electrical abilities were the result of an enhancement made by one of the alien machines. Bo realizes that he is a beacon for the invaders, in order to find and wipe out any remaining humans. He, along with the resistance fighters, need to figure out how to get the bomb near the mother ship before they are all wiped out. \n\n==Cast==\n* [[Lee Pace]] as Bo\n* [[B\u00e9r\u00e9nice Marlohe]] as Nadia\n*[[Jason Flemyng]] as Stander the Photo journalist\n* Sibulele Gcilitshana as Kara, rebel\n*Wandile Molebatsi as Roderick\n*Sekoati Sk Tsubane as Juma\n*Leroy Gopal as Jeandre\n*Welile Nzunza as Cedric\n*Patrick Bakoba as Kenyan Captain\n*Tom Fairfoot as Lieutenant Smalls\n*Ben Tjibe as Lookout\n*Chantal Herman as Female Medic\n*Barileng Malebye as Young Soldier\n*Jabulani Mthembu as Poacher 1\n*Batsile Ramasodi as Poacher 2\n*Phoenix Baaitse as Father\n*Bethel Dube as Daughter\n*Reabetsoe Machepha as Smallest Boy\n* Kenneth Fok as Asian Journalist\n* Alan Santini as Soldier one\n* Edwin Jay as Soldier\n* Noko \"Flow\" Mabitsela as Kenyan boy\n* Barileng Malebye as Young Kenyan soldier\n* Ingmar B\u00fcchner as Soldier\n* Carl Roddam as Soldier\n* Steven Ward as Soldier two\n\n== Development ==\n\n=== Pre-Production ===\nOriginally titled as \"Prisoner of War,\" Revolt entered pre-production with an enthusiastic Joe Miale (director, co-writer), quoted by [[Deadline Hollywood|Deadline]]'s journalist Mike Flemming Jr., saying, \"Alien war machines have been stomping around in my head for far too long.\"<ref>{{cite web|title=Cannes: Voltage Brings \u2018Prisoner Of War\u2019 To Croisette|url=https://deadline.com/2014/05/cannes-voltage-brings-prisoner-of-war-to-croisette-727868/?utm_source=dlvr.it&utm_medium=twitter|website=[[DEADLINE]]|publisher=deadline.com|access-date=20 April 2020}}</ref>\n\nBrian Kavanaugh-Jones, the producer for Automatik, along with Zev Foreman and Nicolas Chartier, producers for Voltage, expressed enthusiasm for Miale's vision for \"Prisoner of War.\" In an interview with Deadline magazine, Chartier expressed, \"We are firm believers in Joe Miale\u2019s vision and look forward to establishing a new science-fiction franchise with him.\u201d \n\n[[Alex Russell (actor)|Alex Russell]] was to originally to play Bo but [[Lee Pace]] ended up with the lead role for undisclosed reasons. \n\n=== Production ===\nProduction officially kicked off on September of 2014 on site in [[Johannesburg|Johannesburg, South Africa]]. \n\n== Reception ==\n\n=== Release  ===\nThe film premiered on July 1st 2017 in Japan. It was later released on the web in the Netherlands on the 6th, in Thai theaters on the 27th, in Singaporean theaters on the 28th of September in the same year, and final release in limited locations in the United States on the 17th of November, also in the same year. The film was released in DVD format on the 4th of December of 2017.<ref>{{cite web|title=REVOLT 2017|url=https://www.imdb.com/title/tt3722614/?ref_=ttexst_exst_tt\\|website=[[IMDb]]|publisher=imdb.com|access-date=20 April 2020}}</ref>\n\n=== Charity ===\nAccording to [[The Hollywood Reporter]], for the first time in the history of Hollywood, the production companies of \"Revolt\" ([[Voltage Pictures]], Automatik, and 42 Productions) launched an [[Indiegogo|IndieGoGo]] campaign for $15,000. The money was used to give back to the generous people of a town near [[Johannesburg]] who helped out during production. The companies matched every dollar in the campaign in order to build a football field, drug counseling, a car wash, among other projects.<ref>{{cite web|title='Revolt' Producers Launch Crowdfunding Campaign to Aid South African Township (Exclusive)|url=https://www.hollywoodreporter.com/news/revolt-producers-launch-crowdfunding-campaign-780267|website=[[The Hollywood Reporter]]|publisher=hollywoodreporter.com|access-date=20 April 2020}}</ref>\n\n=== Critical Response ===\nA day before its U.S. theatrical release, the Los Angeles Times released a review on \"Revolt.\" Gary Goldstein, the author of the article, wrote, \"in 'Revolt,' a propulsive, no-nonsense sci-fi thriller that\u2019s far more watchable than its generic title may imply.\"\"<ref>{{cite web|title=Review: \u2018Revolt\u2019 delivers a swift, satisfying alien invasion|url=https://www.latimes.com/entertainment/movies/la-et-mn-capsule-revolt-review-20171116-story.html|website=[[Los Angeles Times]]|publisher=latimes.com|access-date=22 April 2020}}</ref>\n\nA few reviews from select sites are positive. However, overall, the response to \"Revolt\" is mostly moderate. \"Revolt\" has a 41% positive rating on Rotten Tomatoes along with a 5.2/10 star rating on IMDb. \n\nA common theme among reviews is a criticism on the use of many sci-fi clich\u00e9s while, according to review websites like Frame Rated and Screen Anarchy, still \"interesting enough to remain watchable.\"<ref>{{cite web|title=Review: REVOLT, a Massive Case of Deja Vu|url=https://screenanarchy.com/2017/11/review-revolt-a-massive-case-of-deja-vu.html|website=[[SCREENANARCHY]]|publisher=screenanarchy.com|access-date=22 April 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=REVOLT (2017)|url=https://www.framerated.co.uk/revolt-2017/|website=[[FRAMERATED]]|publisher=framerated.co.uk|access-date=22 April 2020}}</ref>\n\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist|30em}}\n\n==External links==\n* {{IMDb title|3722614}}\n* {{rotten_tomatoes|revolt_2017}}\n\n[[Category:2017 films]]\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox film\n| name           = Revolt\n| image          = Revolt (film poster).jpg\n| alt            = \n| caption        = Theatrical release poster\n| director       = Joe Miale\n| producer       = {{Plainlist|\n* Rory Aitken\n* Nicolas Chartier\n* Zev Foreman\n* James Harris\n* Brian Kavanaugh-Jones\n* Ben Pugh\n}}\n| writer         = {{Plainlist|\n* Rowan Athale\n* Joe Miale\n}}\n| starring       = {{Plainlist|\n* [[Lee Pace]]\n* [[B\u00e9r\u00e9nice Marlohe]]}}\n| music          = [[Bear McCreary]]\n|