erall, the response to \"Revolt\" is mostly moderate. \"Revolt\" has a 41% positive rating on Rotten Tomatoes along with a 5.2/10 star rating on IMDB. \n\nA common theme among reviews is a criticism on the use of many sci-fi clich\u00e9s while, according to review websites like Frame Rated and Screen Anarchy, still \"interesting enough to remain watchable.\"<ref>{{cite web|title=Review: REVOLT, a Massive Case of Deja Vu|url=https://screenanarchy.com/2017/11/review-revolt-a-massive-case-of-deja-vu.html|website=[[SCREENANARCHY]]|publisher=screenanarchy.com|access-date=22 April 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=REVOLT (2017)|url=https://www.framerated.co.uk/revolt-2017/|website=[[FRAMERATED]]|publisher=framerated.co.uk|access-date=22 April 2020}}</ref>\n\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist|30em}}\n\n==External links==\n* {{IMDb title|3722614}}\n* {{rotten_tomatoes|revolt_2017}}\n\n[[Category:2017 films]]\n", "name_user": "Wbm1058", "label": "safe", "comment": "IMDb(viaWP:JWB)", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Revolt_(film)"}
{"title_page": "Chinese Peruvians", "text_new": "{{infobox ethnic group\n| group            = Chinese Peruvians<br />{{small|\u79d8\u9c81\u534e\u4eba\uff08\u79d8\u9c81\u4e2d\u56fd\u4eba\uff09}}<br />{{small|'''Tus\u00e1n (\u571f\u751f\uff09'''}}\n| pop              = '''est. 6,400,000'''<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.panoramas.pitt.edu/health-and-society/chinatown-peru-brief-look-chinese-diaspora-latin-america|title=Chinatown in Peru? A Brief Look of the Chinese Diaspora in Latin America|website=www.panoramas.pitt.edu|accessdate=Oct 8, 2017}}</ref><br>\n''Around 20.1% of Peru\u2019s population have at least one Chinese immigrant ancestor''\n| popplace         = [[Lima]], [[Huacho]], [[Ica, Peru|Ica]], [[Piura]], [[Huancayo]], [[Cusco]], [[Moyobamba]], [[Tarapoto]], [[Iquitos]].\n| langs            = [[Peruvian Spanish]], [[Quechuan languages|Quechua]], [[Mandarin Chinese|Mandarin]], [[Hakka Chinese|Hakka]], [[Yue Chinese|Cantonese]], [[Hokkien Chinese|Hokkien]], others\n| rels             = [[Roman Catholicism]], [[Buddhism]], [[Chinese folk religion]]\n| related          = [[Asian Latin Americans]], [[Asian Peruvians]]\n| native_name      = \n| native_name_lang = zh\n| flag             = [[File:Flag of the People's Republic of China.svg|50px]]   [[File:Flag of Peru.svg|50px]]\n| image            = [[File:Condecoran al Presidente de la Rep\u00fablica Popular China (31128355276).jpg|220px]]\n| image_caption    = PRC [[President (government title)|President]] [[Xi Jinping]] in the [[Congress of Peru]] in a foreign relations trip to [[Peru]]\n| total_year       = 2017\n}}\n{{Infobox Chinese\n|s = \u79d8\u9c81\u534e\u4fa8\u534e\u4eba |t = {{linktext|\u79d8\u9b6f|\u83ef\u50d1|\u83ef\u4eba}}\n  |p = B\u00ecl\u01d4 Hu\u00e1qi\u00e1o Hu\u00e1r\u00e9n\n  |j = bei<sup>3</sup>lou<sup>5</sup> waa<sup>4</sup>kiu<sup>4</sup> waa<sup>4</sup>jan<sup>4</sup>\n|altname = Tus\u00e1n\n|c2 = {{linktext|lang=zh|\u571f\u751f}}\n  |p2 = t\u01d4 sh\u0113ng\n  |j2 = tou<sup>2</sup> saang<sup>1</sup>\n|l2 = Local-born\n}}\n'''Chinese Peruvians''', also known as '''''tus\u00e1n''''' (a [[loanword]] from {{zh|c=\u571f\u751f|p=t\u01d4 sh\u0113ng|j=tou2 saang1|l=local born}}), are members of a Peruvian ethnic group whose ancestors came from [[Guangdong Province]] in China. They are people of [[Overseas Chinese]] ancestry born in [[Peru]] or who have made Peru their adopted homeland.\n\nMost Chinese Peruvians are multilingual. In addition to [[Spanish language|Spanish]] or [[Quechua language|Quechua]], many of them speak one or more [[varieties of Chinese]] that may include [[Mandarin Chinese|Mandarin]], [[Yue Chinese|Cantonese]], [[Hakka Chinese|Hakka]], and [[Min Nan|Minnan]] ([[Hokkien]]).\n\nOutside of the predominant [[Indigenous peoples in Peru|Amerindian]], [[Peruvians#Mestizos|mestizo]], and [[Peruvians of European descent|white]] populations, [[Afro-Peruvian|black]], [[Japanese Peruvians|Japanese]], Chinese, and others are estimated to constitute 3% of the Peruvian population.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.cia.gov/library/publications/the-world-factbook/geos/pe.html|title=The World Factbook: Peru: People and society|website=www.cia.gov|accessdate=31 August 2017}}</ref> Other sources estimate that the population of Peruvians with Chinese ancestry is as high as 20% when people of mixed heritage are included in the statistics.{{Citation needed|date=February 2020}}\n\n==History==\n\n===Early history===\n[[File:INAUGURACI\u00d3N DE MUESTRA FOTOGR\u00c1FICA SOBRE INICIOS DE INMIGRACI\u00d3N CHINA AL PER\u00da EN PABELL\u00d3N NACIONAL EN EXPO SHANGHAI (4740716643).jpg|thumb|Peru and China celebrate 160th anniversary of diplomatic ties]]\n[[File:Chinese_laborers_in_Peru.jpg|thumb|Chinese laborers in Peru - 1890]]\nAsian [[coolies]] who were shipped from the [[Spanish Philippines]] to [[Acapulco]] via the [[Manila galleon|Manila-Acapulco galleons]] were all called ''Chino'' (\"Chinese\"), although in reality they were not only from China but also other places, including what are today the [[Philippines]] itself, [[Japan]], [[Malaysia]], [[Indonesia]], [[East Timor]], and further afield such as [[India]] and [[Sri Lanka]].<ref name=\"LaiTan2010\">{{cite book|editor1=Walton Look Lai|editor2=Chee Beng Tan|title=The Chinese in Latin America and the Caribbean|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=xrGShVU6VrgC&pg=PA12|accessdate=8 January 2016|year=2010|publisher=BRILL|isbn=90-04-18213-6}}</ref>{{rp|12}}<ref name=\"Herrera-Sobek2012\">{{cite book|editor=Mar\u00eda Herrera-Sobek|title=Celebrating Latino Folklore: An Encyclopedia of Cultural Traditions|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=bDIwZ8BieWcC&pg=PA59|accessdate=8 January 2016|volume=1|year=2012|publisher=ABC-CLIO|isbn=978-0-313-34339-1|page=59}}</ref><ref name=\"Binder1993\">{{cite book|editor=Wolfgang Binder|title=Slavery in the Americas|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=M25cDaIsFNYC&pg=PA100|accessdate=8 January 2016|volume=4|year=1993|publisher=K\u00f6nigshausen & Neumann|isbn=978-3-88479-713-6|page=100}}</ref><ref name=\"Meagher2008\">{{cite book|author=Arnold J. Meagher|title=The Coolie Trade: The Traffic in Chinese Laborers to Latin America 1847-1874|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=H7dBmBsd-XgC&pg=PA194|accessdate=8 January 2016|year=2008|publisher=Arnold J Meagher|isbn=978-1-4363-0943-1|page=194}}</ref> Filipinos made up most of their population.<ref name=\"Russell2009\">{{cite book|author=James W. Russell|title=Class and Race Formation in North America|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=PZgR6ubuUXcC&pg=PA27|accessdate=8 January 2016|year=2009|publisher=University of Toronto Press|isbn=978-0-8020-9678-4|page=27}}</ref> The people in this community of diverse Asians in [[Mexico]] were called \"los indios chinos\" by the Spanish.<ref>{{cite journal|format=PDF|url=http://148.202.18.157/sitios/publicacionesite/pperiod/Lhistoricas/pdfs/vol1/4.pdf|title=El alcalde de los chinos en la provincia de Colima durante el siglo xvii: un sistema de representaci\u00f3n en torno a un oficio|trans-title=The mayor of the Chinese in the province of Colima during the seventeenth century: a system of representation surrounding trade|language=es|journal=Letras Hist\u00f3ricas|first=Claudia Paulina|last=Machuca Ch\u00e1vez|date=Autumn\u2013Winter 2009|issue=1|publisher=Ciesas Occidente|pages=95\u2013116|url-status=dead|archiveurl= https://web.archive.org/web/20140407081131/http://148.202.18.157/sitios/publicacionesite/pperiod/Lhistoricas/pdfs/vol1/4.pdf|archivedate=7 April 2014|df=dmy}}</ref> Most of these workers were male and were obtained from Portuguese traders, who obtained them from [[Portuguese Empire|Portuguese colonial possessions]] and outposts of the [[Estado da India]], which included parts of India, [[Bengal]], [[Malacca]], Indonesia, [[Nagasaki]] in Japan, and [[Macau]].<ref>{{cite journal|format=PDF|first=D\u00e9borah|last=Oropeza Keresey|url=http://www.redalyc.org/pdf/600/60022589001.pdf|title=La Esclavitud Asi\u00e1tica en El Virreinato de La Nueva Espa\u00f1a, 1565-1673|trans-title=Asian Slavery in the Viceroyalty of New Spain, 1565-1673|language=es|journal=Historia Mexicana|volume=LXI|date=July{{ndash}}September 2011|accessdate=31 August 2017|issue=1|publisher=El Colegio de M\u00e9xico|issn=0185-0172|pages=20\u201321}}</ref><ref>{{cite journal|format=PDF|first=D\u00e9borah|last=Oropeza|url=http://www.mexicanistas.eu/uploads/Ideas%20centrales%20en%20torno%20a%20la%20esclavitud%20asiatica%20en%20la%20Nueva%20Espana,%20Deborah%20Oropeza.pdf|title=Ideas centrales en torno a la esclavitud asi\u00e1tica en la Nueva Espa\u00f1a|trans-title=Central ideas surrounding Asian slavery in New Spain|language=es|journal=Historia Mexicana|date=Fall{{ndash}}Winter 2009|issue=1|publisher=Encuentro de Mexicanistas 2010 (La esclavitud asi\u00e1tica en el virreinato de la Nueva Espa\u00f1a, 1565-1673)|page=2|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140407092442/http://www.mexicanistas.eu/uploads/Ideas%20centrales%20en%20torno%20a%20la%20esclavitud%20asiatica%20en%20la%20Nueva%20Espana%2C%20Deborah%20Oropeza.pdf|archivedate=7 April 2014}}</ref> [[Chinese people in Spain|Spain received some of these coolies]] from Mexico, where owning a ''Chino'' coolie showed high status.<ref name=\"LaiTan2010\"/>{{rp|13}} Records of three Japanese coolies dating from the 16th century, named Gaspar Fernandes, Miguel and Ventura who ended up in Mexico showed that they were purchased by Portuguese slave traders in Japan, brought to Manila from where they were shipped to Mexico by their owner Perez.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://news.asiaone.com/News/AsiaOne+News/Asia/Story/A1Story20130514-422430.html|title=Japanese slaves taken to Mexico in 16th century|work=[[Yomiuri Shimbun]]|via=Asiaone News|date=14 May 2013|accessdate=8 January 2016|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20161022120120/http://news.asiaone.com/News/AsiaOne+News/Asia/Story/A1Story20130514-422430.html|archivedate=22 October 2016}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|first=Ida|last=Torres|url=http://japandailypress.com/records-show-japanese-slaves-crossed-the-pacific-to-mexico-in-16th-century-1428777/|title=Records show Japanese slaves crossed the Pacific to Mexico in 16th century|newspaper=Japan Daily Press|date=14 May 2013|accessdate=8 January 2016|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160131111645/http://japandailypress.com/records-show-japanese-slaves-crossed-the-pacific-to-mexico-in-16th-century-1428777/|archivedate=31 January 2016}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|author=Preston Phro|title=To Mexico in Chains: The Tale of Three 16th Century Japanese Slaves|url=http://en.rocketnews24.com/2013/05/15/to-mexico-in-chains-the-tale-of-three-16th-century-japanese-slaves/|newspaper=Rocket News 24|date=15 May 2013|accessdate=8 January 2016}}</ref> Some of these Asian slaves were also brought to [[Lima]] in [[Peru]], where it was recorded that in 1613 there was a small community of Asians, consisting of Chinese, Japanese, Filipinos, Malays, Cambodians and others.<ref name=\"Bethell1984\">{{cite book|editor=Leslie Bethell|title=The Cambridge History of Latin America|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=hhNfVshMw64C&pg=PA21|accessdate=8 January 2016|series=Colonial Latin America|volume=II|year=1984|publisher=Cambridge University Press|isbn=978-0-521-24516-6|page=21}}</ref><ref name=\"L\u00f3pez-Calvo2013\">{{cite book|author=Ignacio L\u00f3pez-Calvo|title=The Affinity of the Eye: Writing Nikkei in Peru|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=mMY4-ffumwUC&pg=PA134|accessdate=8 January 2016|year=2013|publisher=University of Arizona Press|isbn=978-0-8165-9987-5|page=134}}</ref><ref name=\"Hoerder2002\">{{cite book|author=Dirk Hoerder|title=Cultures in Contact: World Migrations in the Second Millennium|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=1PDVdU4YZWgC&pg=PA200|accessdate=8 January 2016|year=2002|publisher=Duke University Press|isbn=0-8223-8407-8|page=200}}</ref><ref name=\"Cauti2005\">{{cite book|author=Fernando Iwasaki Cauti|title=Extremo Oriente y el Per\u00fa en el siglo XVI|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=tPwCeavlP9QC&pg=PA293|accessdate=8 January 2016|year=2005|publisher=Fondo Editorial PUCP|isbn=978-9972-42-671-1|page=293}}</ref>\n\nChinese [[Immigration|immigrants]], who in the 19th century took a four-month trip from Macau (then a Portuguese territory), settled as [[Employment|contract labor]]ers or coolies. Other Chinese coolies from [[Guangdong]] followed.\n80,000<ref name=smithbodies>{{cite web |last1=Katz |first1=Brigit |title=Remains of 19th-Century Chinese Laborers Found at a Pyramid in Peru |url=https://web.archive.org/web/20191111084210/https://www.smithsonianmag.com/smart-news/remains-19th-century-chinese-laborers-found-pyramid-peru-180964647/ |website=Smithsonian.com}}</ref> to 100,000<ref name=brownsla>{{cite web |last1=Hwang |first1=Justina |title=Chinese in Peru in the 19th century |url=https://web.archive.org/web/20191111084324/https://library.brown.edu/create/modernlatinamerica/chapters/chapter-6-the-andes/moments-in-andean-history/chinese-peru/ |website=Brown University}}</ref><ref name=smithbodies/> Chinese contract laborers, 95% of which were Cantonese and almost all of which were male, were sent mostly to the [[sugar]] plantations from 1849 to 1874, during the termination of [[slavery]]. They were to provide continuous labor for the coastal [[guano]] mines and especially for the coastal plantations where they became a major labor force (contributing greatly to the Peruvian [[Guano Era|guano boom]]) until the end of the century. While the coolies were believed to be reduced to virtual slaves, they also represented a historical transition from slave to free labor. A third group of Chinese workers was contracted for the construction of the railway from Lima to [[La Oroya]] and [[Huancayo]]. Chinese migrants were barred from using cemeteries reserved for Roman Catholics, and were instead buried at pre-Incan burial sites.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://phys.org/news/2017-08-peru-pre-incan-site-tomb-chinese.html |quote=The Chinese were discriminated against even in death, having to be buried in the pre-Incan sites after being barred from cemeteries reserved for Roman Catholics. |title=Peru discovers in pre-Incan site tomb of 16 Chinese migrants |date=August 24, 2017 |publisher=[[Phys.org]]}}</ref> Between 1849 and 1874 half<ref name=brownsla/><ref name=smithbodies/> the Chinese population of Peru perished due to abuse, exhaustion, and suicide<ref name=brownsla/> caused by forced labor.<ref name=brownsla/><ref name=smithbodies/>\n\n[[File:CDO Cienguilla.jpg|thumb|250px|left| Chinese school in Peru]]\n[[File:Chinatown, Lima20060002.JPG|thumb|250px|left| Chinatown in Lima]]\n[[File:Danza del le\u00f3n cdo.jpg|thumb|250px|left| Chinese Community in Peru - Dance of the Lion]]\nThere were almost no women among the nearly entirely male Chinese coolie population that migrated to Peru and Cuba.<ref name=\"LaiTan2010\"/>{{rp|143}}<ref name=\"McKeown2001\">{{cite book|author=Adam McKeown|author-link=Adam McKeown|title=Chinese Migrant Networks and Cultural Change: Peru, Chicago, and Hawaii 1900-1936|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=vix_3doZkH0C&pg=PA47|accessdate=8 January 2016|year=2001|publisher=University of Chicago Press|isbn=978-0-226-56025-0|page=47}}</ref> Peruvian women were married to these Chinese male migrants.<ref>{{cite book|page=[https://archive.org/details/orientalsasianam0000leer/page/75 75]|pages=|year=1999|accessdate=May 17, 2014|publisher=Temple University Press|volume=|author=Robert G. Lee|location=|title=Orientals: Asian Americans in Popular Culture|url=https://archive.org/details/orientalsasianam0000leer|url-access=registration|quote=chinese peruvian women.|isbn=1439905711}}</ref><ref name=\"Tan2004\">{{cite book|author=Chee-Beng Tan|title=Chinese Overseas: Comparative Cultural Issues|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=Ca7UAQAAQBAJ&pg=PA47|accessdate=8 January 2016|year=2004|publisher=Hong Kong University Press|isbn=978-962-209-661-5|page=47}}</ref><ref name=\"LeeLim\">{{cite book|author1=Josephine D. Lee|author2=Imogene L. Lim|author3=Yuko Matsukawa|title=Re/collecting Early Asian America: Essays in Cultural History|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=fjeAaEqo-CEC&pg=PA181|publisher=Temple University Press|isbn=978-1-4399-0120-5|pages=181\u2013}}</ref><ref name=\"Lai1998\">{{cite book|author=Walton Look Lai|title=The Chinese in the West Indies, 1806-1995: A Documentary History|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=fMrit6tcO_AC&pg=PA8|accessdate=8 January 2016|year=1998|publisher=University of the West Indies Press|isbn=978-976-640-021-7|page=8}}</ref><ref name=\"Gonzales2014\">{{cite book|author=Michael J. Gonzales|title=Plantation Agriculture and Social Control in Northern Peru, 1875\u20131933|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=oKt0BQAAQBAJ&pg=PT139|accessdate=8 January 2016|year=2014|publisher=University of Texas Press|isbn=978-1-4773-0602-4|page=139}}</ref> [[Africa]]n women particularly had mostly no intercourse with Chinese men during their labor as coolies, while Chinese had contact with Peruvian women in cities; there they formed relationships and sired mixed babies. These women originated from Andean and coastal areas and did not originally come from the cities; in the haciendas on the coast in rural areas, native young women of ''ind\u00edgenas'' (\"native\") and ''serranas'' (\"mountain\") origin from the [[Andes]] mountains would come down to work. These Andean native women were favored over Africans as marital partners by Chinese men, with matchmakers arranging for communal marriages of Chinese men to young ''ind\u00edgenas'' and ''serranas''.<ref>{{cite book|page=144|pages=|year=2010|accessdate=May 17, 2014|publisher=BRILL|volume=|author=Isabelle Lausent-Herrera|editor1=Walton Look Lai|editor2=Chee Beng Tan|quote=|location=|title=The Chinese in Latin America and the Caribbean|series=Brill ebook titles|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=xrGShVU6VrgC&pg=PA144#v=onepage&q&f=false|isbn=9004182136}}</ref> There was a racist reaction by Peruvians to the marriages of Peruvian women and Chinese men.<ref>{{cite book|page=145|pages=|year=2010|accessdate=May 17, 2014|publisher=BRILL|volume=|author=Isabelle Lausent-Herrera|editor1=Walton Look Lai|editor2=Chee Beng Tan|quote=|location=|title=The Chinese in Latin America and the Caribbean|series=Brill ebook titles|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=xrGShVU6VrgC&pg=PA145#v=onepage&q&f=false|isbn=9004182136}}</ref> When native Peruvian women (''cholas et natives'', ''Indias'', ''ind\u00edgenas'') and Chinese men had mixed children, the children were called ''injerto''; once these ''injertos'' emerged, Chinese men sought out girls of ''injerta'' origin as marriage partners. Children born to black mothers were not called ''injertos''.<ref>{{cite book|page=146|pages=|year=2010|accessdate=May 17, 2014|publisher=BRILL|volume=|author=Isabelle Lausent-Herrera|editor1=Walton Look Lai|editor2=Chee Beng Tan|quote=|location=|title=The Chinese in Latin America and the Caribbean|series=Brill ebook titles|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=xrGShVU6VrgC&pg=PA146#v=onepage&q&f=false|isbn=9004182136}}</ref> Peruvians of low class established sexual unions or marriages with the Chinese men, and some black and Indian women \"bred\" with the Chinese according to Alfredo Sachett\u00ed, who claimed the mixing was causing the Chinese to suffer from \"progressive degeneration\". In Casa Grande, highland Indian women and Chinese men participated in communal \"mass marriages\" with each other, arranged when highland women were brought by a Chinese matchmaker after receiving a down payment.<ref>{{cite book|page=|pages=|year=2014|accessdate=May 17, 2014|publisher=University of Texas Press|volume=|author=Michael J. Gonzales|quote=|location=|title=Plantation Agriculture and Social Control in Northern Peru, 1875\u20131933|series=|url=https://books.google.com/?id=oKt0BQAAQBAJ&pg=PT139&dq=chinese+peru+women#v=onepage&q=chinese%20peru%20women&f=false|isbn=1477306021}}</ref><ref>{{cite book|page=100|pages=|year=1985|accessdate=May 17, 2014|publisher=University of Texas Press|issue=Issue 62 of Latin American Monographs, No 62, Issue 62 of Institute of Latin American Studies|volume=Volume 62 of Texas Pan American Series|author=Michael J. Gonzales|quote=|location=|title=Plantation Agriculture and Social Control in Northern Peru, 1875-1933|series=Brill ebook titles|url=https://books.google.com/?id=I6-zAAAAIAAJ&q=when+recruits+arrived+placed+room+grooms+lined+up+opposite+highland+women+faces+each+directly+opposite+woman+contractor+claps+hand+signal+turn+around+man+wife+permits&dq=when+recruits+arrived+placed+room+grooms+lined+up+opposite+highland+women+faces+each+directly+opposite+woman+contractor+claps+hand+signal+turn+around+man+wife+permits|isbn=029276491X}}</ref>\n\nIn Peru and [[Cuba]], some Indian (Native American), [[mulatto]], black, and white women engaged in carnal relations or marriages with Chinese men, with marriages of mulatto, black, and white woman being reported by the Cuba Commission Report. In Peru, it was reported by ''[[The New York Times]]'' that [[Women in Peru|Peruvian black and Indian (Native) women]] married Chinese men to their own advantage and to the disadvantage of the men since they dominated and \"subjugated\" the Chinese men despite the fact that the labor contract was annulled by the marriage, reversing the roles in marriage with the Peruvian woman holding marital power, ruling the family and making the Chinese men slavish, docile, \"servile\", \"submissive\" and \"feminine\" and commanding them around, reporting that \"Now and then...he [the Chinese man] becomes enamored of the charms of some sombre-hued chola (Native Indian and mestiza woman) or samba (mixed black woman), and is converted and joins the Church, so that may enter the bonds of wedlock with the dusky se\u00f1orita.\"<ref name=\"Young2014\">{{cite book|author=Elliott Young|title=Alien Nation: Chinese Migration in the Americas from the Coolie Era Through World War II|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=ch8VBQAAQBAJ&pg=PA82|accessdate=8 January 2016|series=David J. Weber Series in the New Borderlands History|volume=4: Wiley Blackwell Concise History of the Modern World|year=2014|publisher=UNC Press Books|isbn=978-1-4696-1296-6|page=82}}</ref> Chinese men were sought out as husbands and considered a \"catch\" by the \"dusky damsels\" (Peruvian women) because they were viewed as a \"model husband, hard-working, affectionate, faithful and obedient\" and \"handy to have in the house\", the Peruvian women became the \"better half\" instead of the \"weaker vessel\" and would command their Chinese husbands \"around in fine style\" instead of treating them equally, while the labor contract of the Chinese coolie would be nullified by the marriage, the Peruvian wife viewed the nullification merely as the previous \"master\" handing over authority over the Chinese man to her as she became his \"mistress\", keeping him in \"servitude\" to her, speedily ending any complaints and suppositions by the Chinese men that they would have any power in the marriage.<ref>{{cite web|format=PDF|title=The Coolie Trade: The slavery of the present - The traffic of Peru - Hiring of the Coolie - Horrors of the middle passage the Coolie's fate|url=https://www.nytimes.com/1873/07/19/archives/the-coolie-trade-the-slavery-of-the-present-the-traffic-of-peru.html|date=28 June 1873|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150701053253/http://query.nytimes.com/mem/archive-free/pdf?res=9B0DE2D61539EF34BC4152DFB1668388669FDE|newspaper=New York Times|accessdate=17 May 2014|archivedate=1 July 2015}}</ref>\n\nAlthough Chinese Peruvians were well-integrated to Peruvian society, it did not come with an easy beginning. During the [[War of the Pacific]], Chinese labors led an uprising in support to Chile against Peru. Peruvians held Chinese as responsible to the Chilean invading army, and this led to the first ever [[Sinophobia]] in Latin America. Chinese were targeted and murdered by native Peruvians and it was not until 1890s that anti-Chinese [[pogroms]] stopped.<ref name=\"Taylor\">Taylor, Lewis. Indigenous Peasant Rebellions in Peru during the 1880s</ref><ref name=\"bonilla\">Bonilla, Heraclio. 1978. The National and Colonial Problem in Peru. ''[[Past & Present (journal)|Past and Present]]''</ref> Despite this, Chinese were barred from immigrating to the country until 1970s.<ref>[https://books.google.com/books?id=OP-EBAAAQBAJ&pg=PA87&lpg=PA87&dq=sinophobia+peru&source=bl&ots=hJsiEwA8Xe&sig=LVE_M83bDe-Mm2igEeTSldf_O4I&hl=en&sa=X&ved=0ahUKEwj4_L72g-vaAhWJurwKHb1ZBrIQ6AEIMDAB#v=onepage&q=sinophobia%20peru&f=false/ Dragons in the Land of the Condor: Writing Tus\u00e1n in Peru]</ref>\n\nAnother group of Chinese settlers came after the founding of [[Sun Yat-sen]]'s republic in 1912, and another after the establishment of [[Communist Party of China|Communist rule]] in 1949.\n\nIn 1957, Cantonese speakers constituted 85 per cent of the total Chinese immigrant population, the rest of whom were Hakka speakers.<ref>{{cite book|title=Ch\u02bbiao|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=XdocAQAAMAAJ|volume=3, Issue 2|year=1974|publisher=Basement Workshop, Incorporated|page=35|chapter=The Chinese in Peru|quote=\"...but in 1957 speakers of Cantonese constituted 85 per cent of the total, the rest of whom were Hakka speakers.\"}}</ref>\n\n{{Culture of Peru}}\n\n===Modern-day immigration===\nRecent Chinese immigrants settled in Peru from [[Hong Kong]] and Macau in 1997 and 1999, owing to fear of those territories returning to Communist rule, while others have come from other places in [[mainland China]], [[Taiwan]], and southeast Asian Chinese communities, including those of Malaysia, Indonesia, [[Singapore]] and the Philippines. Many [[Chinese Indonesian]]s came to Peru after anti-Chinese [[May 1998 riots of Indonesia|riot]]s and [[massacre]]s in those countries in the 1960s, 1970s, and late 1990s. These recent Chinese immigrants make Peru currently the home of the largest ethnically Chinese community in [[Latin America]].\n\n===Emigration===\nMany Chinese Peruvians left Peru in the 1960s and 1970s. Most of them headed to the [[United States]], where they were called [[Chinese American]]s or Peruvian Americans of Chinese descent, while others went to [[Canada]], [[Spain]], mainland China, Hong Kong, Macau, Taiwan, [[Australia]], or [[New Zealand]].{{Citation needed|date=December 2011}}\n\n===Role in the economy===\nAfter their contracts ended, many of them adopted the last name of their patrons (one of the reasons that many Chinese Peruvians carry Spanish last names). Some freed coolies (and later immigrants) established many small businesses. These included ''chifas'' (Chinese-Peruvian restaurants - the word is derived from Chinese term, {{linktext|lang=zh-Hant|\u5403\u98ef}} ({{zh|j=ci<sup>3</sup>faan<sup>6</sup> |p=ch\u012bf\u00e0n}}) which means \"to eat rice or to have a meal\"). Calle Cap\u00f3n, [[Chinatown, Lima|Lima's Chinatown]], also known as Barrio Chino de Lima, became one of the [[Western Hemisphere]]'s earliest Chinatowns. The Chinese coolies married Peruvian women, and many Chinese Peruvians today are of mixed Chinese, Spanish, African or [[Indigenous peoples of the Americas|Native American]] descent. Chinese Peruvians also assisted in the building of railroad and development of the [[Amazon Rainforest]], where they tapped rubber trees, washed gold, cultivated rice, and traded with the natives. They even became the largest foreign colony in the Amazon capital of [[Iquitos]] by the end of the century.\n\n==Notable people==\nThe vast majority of Chinese descendants in Peru do not carry a Chinese surname, since their ancestors, when they arrived in Peru, were baptized or adopted the surnames of their patrons, Catholic saints or some very common Castilian surname. \n\n=== Politics & business ===\n{|\n|\n* Ephraim Wong Lu <small> (businessman) </small>\n* Enrique Wong <small> (congressman) </small>\n* Erasmus Wong Lu <small> (businessman) </small>\n* Erick Chuy <small> (businessman, accountant, missionary) </small>\n* Eugenio Chang Cruz <small> (lawyer, professor and senator) </small>\n*Felipe Tam Fox <small> (administrator, official and former head of the SBS) </small>\n*[[Humberto Lay Sun]] <small> (congressman) </small>\n*Isabel Wong-Vargas <small> (businesswoman) </small>\n*Jes\u00fas Wu <small> (businessman) </small>\n*[[Jos\u00e9 Antonio Chang]] <small> (industrial and political engineer) </small>\n|\n*Juan Pablo Chang Navarro <small> (politician) </small>\n*Julio Ch\u00e1vez Chiong <small> (mayor) </small>\n* Julio Ch\u00fa M\u00e9riz <small> (politician) </small>\n* Luis Chang Reyes <small> (engineer and politician) </small>\n* Magdalena Ch\u00fa <small> (Statistical expert and former head of the  [[National Office of Electoral Processes|ONPE]]) </small>\n* Nelson Chui Mej\u00eda <small> (former president of the Lima Region) </small>\n*Rolando Martel Chang <small> (Superior Judge of Lima and professor) </small>\n* Rosario L\u00f3pez Wong <small> (Superior Criminal Prosecutor of Lima) </small>\n*Rub\u00e9n Chang Gamarra <small> (lawyer and politician) </small>\n|}\n\n=== Entertainment ===\n{|\n|\n* A\u00edda Tam Fox <small> (poet and historian of Peruvian cuisine) </small>\n* Alberto Ku King <small> (journalist) </small>\n* Annie Yep <small> (TV host, journalist, and model) </small>\n* Anthony Choy <small> (lawyer and investigative journalist ufologist) </small>\n* Antonio Wong Rengifo <small> (film director) </small>\n* Sui Yun (Katty Wong) <small> (poet) </small>\n* Jonatan Relayze Chiang <small> (filmmaker) </small>\n* Julio Villanueva Chang <small> (journalist)</small>\n|\n* Mar\u00eda In\u00e9s Ching <small> (journalist) </small>\n* Miguel Yi Carrillo <small> (journalist) </small>\n* Milly Ahon Olgu\u00edn <small> (cultural historian) </small>\n*M\u00f3nica Chang <small> (journalist) </small>\n*[[Patty Wong]] <small> (model and TV presenter) </small>\n* Pedro Mo <small> (rapper) </small>\n*Ra\u00fal Chang Ruiz <small> (journalist, director of the Oriental Magazine) </small>\n|}\n\n=== Athletics ===\n{|\n|\n* Augusto Yep <small> (footballer) </small>\n* [[Edwin V\u00e1squez Cam]] <small> (Olympic champion in shooting, [[London 1948 Olympics | London 1948]]) </small>\n* [[Freddy Wong]] <small> (skater) </small>\n* H\u00e9ctor Cruz Cheng <small> (soccer player) </small>\n*Iv\u00e1n Miranda Chang <small> (tennis player) </small>\n*Jorge Koochoi Sarmiento <small> (footballer, 8 times national champion) </small>\n|\n* Juan Chang Zevallos <small> (footballer and journalist) </small>\n*Julio Lores Col\u00e1n <small> (footballer) </small>\n*[[Katherine Miranda Chang]] <small> (tennis player) </small>\n*Luis Pau Le\u00f3n <small> (footballer) </small>\n*Mariano Loo Granda <small> (footballer) </small>\n*Patty K\u00fa Flores <small> (tennis player) </small>\n|}\n\n=== Culture ===\n{|\n|\n* Alejandro Chu <small> (archaeologist) </small>\n* Apu-Rimak <small> (plastic artist) </small>\n* Carolina Chang Tam <small> (keyboard player) </small>\n* Celia Wu Brading <small> (historian and translator) </small>\n* Chez Wong <small> (cook) </small>\n* Emilio Choy Ma <small> (social scientist) </small>\n* Javier Wong <small> (chef) </small>\n|\n* [[Juan Wong Paredes]] <small> (musician) </small>\n* Juan Wong Popolizio <small> (musician) </small>\n* Julio Mau <small> (singer) </small>\n*Mao Wong L\u00f3pez <small> (musician) </small>\n*Marcelo Wong <small> (plastic artist) </small>\n*Rosa Fung Pineda <small> (archaeologist) </small>\n|}\n\n=== Other ===\n{|\n|\n*Alejandro Chung Hern\u00e1ndez <small> (teacher) </small>\n* Alicia Garcia Yi <small> (teacher, CCPCH director) </small>)\n* Eugenio Chang-Rodr\u00edguez <small> (linguist and professor) </small>\n* Jorge C\u00e9liz Kuong <small> (general) </small>\n* Jos\u00e9 Gallardo Ku <small> (economist) </small>\n|\n*Olga Lock Sing <small> (chemical and scientific engineer) </small>\n* \u00d3scar Tang Cruz <small> (physicist and professor) </small>\n*[[Pedro Zulen]] <small> (philosopher and librarian) </small>\n* Ra\u00fal Chau Quispe <small> (Auxiliary Bishop of Lima) </small>\n* Johnny Ching Paravecino <small> (Teacher-Researcher) </small>\n|}\n\n==See also==\n{{Portal|Peru|China}}\n*[[Asian Latin Americans]]\n*[[Chinatown, Lima]]\n*[[Chinatowns in Latin America]]\n*[[History of Peru]]\n*[[Japanese Peruvians]]\n*[[Overseas Chinese]]\n\n==References==\n{{reflist|colwidth=30em}}\n\n==Further reading==\n*{{citation|last=De Trazegnies Granda|first=Fernando|title=En el pa\u00eds de las colinas de arena: reflexiones sobre la inmigraci\u00f3n china en el Per\u00fa del S. XIX desde la perspectiva del derecho|publication-place=Lima|publisher=Pontificia Universidad Cat\u00f3lica del Per\u00fa|year=1994|isbn=978-84-89309-82-1|oclc=31349975}}\n**Translated into Chinese as {{citation|author=\u7af9\u78a7 [Zhu Bi]|author2=\u814a\u6885 [La Mei] |language=zh-Hans |script-title=zh:\u6c99\u56fd\u4e4b\u68a6\uff1a\u5951\u7ea6\u534e\u5de5\u5728\u79d8\u9c81\u7684\u547d\u8fd0 |publisher=\u4e16\u754c\u77e5\u8bc6\u51fa\u7248\u793e [World Affairs Press]|year=1999|isbn=978-7-5012-1182-1|oclc=237047875}}\n*{{citation|last=L\u00f3pez-Calvo|first=Ignacio|title=Dragons in the Land of the Condor: Writing Tus\u00e1n in Peru (University of Arizona Press, 2014)}} \n*{{citation|last=L\u00f3pez-Calvo|first=Ignacio|title=Sino-Peruvian identity and community as prison: Siu Kam Wen\u2019s rendering of self-exploitation and other survival strategies|editor-first=Evelyn|editor-last=Hu-deHart|editor2-first=Kathy|editor2-last=L\u00f3pez|journal=Afro-Hispanic Review|volume=27|issue=1|date=Spring 2008|pages=73\u201390|url=http://ignaciolopezcalvo.blogspot.com/2008/11/sino-peruvian-identity-and-community-as.html}}\n*Lausent-Herrera, Isabelle. \"The Chinese in Peru and the Changing Peruvian Chinese Community(ies).\" In ''Journal of Chinese Overseas'', 7(2011), pp.&nbsp;69\u2013113. Available [http://ilausent.free.fr/chinos/The%20Chinatown%20in%20Peru%20and%20the%20Changing%20Peruvian%20Chinese%20Communities.pdf online].\n\n==External links==\n*[http://www.apch.com.pe/ APCH.com], Asociaci\u00f3n Peruano China (official website)\n*[https://www.newworlder.com/article/18014/origins-lomo-saltado/ Newworlder.com], Origins: Lomo Saltado\n\n{{Immigrant groups in Peru}}\n{{Overseas Chinese}}\n\n[[Category:Asian Peruvian]]\n[[Category:Ethnic groups in Peru]]\n[[Category:Chinese diaspora by country|Peruvian]]\n[[Category:Chinese Latin American]]\n[[Category:Coolie trade]]\n[[Category:Peruvian people of Chinese descent|*]]\n", "text_old": "{{infobox ethnic group\n| group            = Chinese Peruvians<br />{{small|\u79d8\u9c81\u534e\u4eba\uff08\u79d8\u9c81\u4e2d\u56fd\u4eba\uff09}}<br />{{small|'''Tus\u00e1n (\u571f\u751f\uff09'''}}\n| pop              = '''est. 6,400,000'''<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.panoramas.pitt.edu/health-and-society/chinatown-peru-brief-look-chinese-diaspora-latin-america|title=Chinatown in Peru? A Brief Look of the Chinese Diaspora in Latin America|website=www.panoramas.pitt.edu|accessdate=Oct 8, 2017}}</ref><br>\n''Around 20.1% of Peru\u2019s population have at least one Chinese immigrant ancestor''\n| popplace         = [[Lima]], [[Huacho]], [[Ica, Peru|Ica]], [[Piura]], [[Huancayo]], [[Cusco]], [[Moyobamba]], [[Tarapoto]], [[Iquitos]].\n| langs            = [[Peruvian Spanish]], [[Quechuan languages|Quechua]], [[Mandarin Chinese|Mandarin]], [[Hakka Chinese|Hakka]], [[Yue Chinese|Cantonese]], [[Hokkien Chinese|Hokkien]], others\n| rels             = [[Roman Catholicism]], [[Buddhism]], [[Chinese folk religion]]\n| related          = [[Asian Latin Americans]], [[Asian Peruvians]]\n| native_name      = \n| native_name_lang = zh\n| flag             = [[File:Flag of the People's Republic of China.svg|50px]]   [[File:Flag of Peru.svg|50px]]\n| image            = [[File:Condecoran al Presidente de la Rep\u00fablica Popular China (31128355276).jpg|220px]]\n| image_caption    = PRC [[President]] [[Xi Jinping]] in the [[Congress of Peru]] in a foreign relations trip to [[Peru]]\n| total_year       = 2017\n}}\n{{Infobox Chinese\n|s = \u79d8\u9c81\u534e\u4fa8\u534e\u4eba |t = {{linktext|\u79d8\u9b6f|\u83ef\u50d1|\u83ef\u4eba}}\n  |p = B\u00ecl\u01d4 Hu\u00e1qi\u00e1o Hu\u00e1r\u00e9n\n  |j = bei<sup>3</sup>lou<sup>5</sup> waa<sup>4</sup>kiu<sup>4</sup> waa<sup>4</sup>jan<sup>4</sup>\n|altname = Tus\u00e1n\n|c2 = {{linktext|lang=zh|\u571f\u751f}}\n  |p2 = t\u01d4 sh\u0113ng\n  |j2 = tou<sup>2</sup> saang<sup>1</sup>\n|l2 = Local-born\n}}\n'''Chinese Peruvians''', also known as '''''tus\u00e1n''''' (a [[loanword]] from {{zh|c=\u571f\u751f|p=t\u01d4 sh\u0113ng|j=tou2 saang1|l=local born}}), are members of a Peruvian ethnic group whose ancestors came from [[Guangdong Province]] in China. They are people of [[Overseas Chinese]] ancestry born in [[Peru]] or who have made Peru their adopted homeland.\n\nMost Chinese Peruvians are multilingual. In addition to [[Spanish language|Spanish]] or [[Quechua language|Quechua]], many of them speak one or more [[varieties of Chinese]] that may include [[Mandarin Chinese|Mandarin]], [[Yue Chinese|Cantonese]], [[Hakka Chinese|Hakka]], and [[Min Nan|Minnan]] ([[Hokkien]]).\n\nOutside of the predominant [[Indigenous peoples in Peru|Amerindian]], [[Peruvians#Mestizos|mestizo]], and [[Peruvians of European descent|white]] populations, [[Afro-Peruvian|black]], [[Japanese Peruvians|Japanese]], Chinese, and others are estimated to constitute 3% of the Peruvian population.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.cia.gov/library/publications/the-world-factbook/geos/pe.html|title=The World Factbook: Peru: People and society|website=www.cia.gov|accessdate=31 August 2017}}</ref> Other sources estimate that the population of Peruvians with Chinese ancestry is as high as 20% when people of mixed heritage are included in the statistics.{{Citation needed|date=February 2020}}\n\n==History==\n\n===Early history===\n[[File:INAUGURACI\u00d3N DE MUESTRA FOTOGR\u00c1FICA SOBRE INICIOS DE INMIGRACI\u00d3N CHINA AL PER\u00da EN PABELL\u00d3N NACIONAL EN EXPO SHANGHAI (4740716643).jpg|thumb|Peru and China celebrate 160th anniversary of diplomatic ties]]\n[[File:Chinese_laborers_in_Peru.jpg|thumb|Chinese laborers in Peru - 1890]]\nAsian [[coolies]] who were shipped from the [[Spanish Philippines]] to [[Acapulco]] via the [[Manila galleon|Manila-Acapulco galleons]] were all called ''Chino'' (\"Chinese\"), although in reality they were not only from China but also other places, including what are today the [[Philippines]] itself, [[Japan]], [[Malaysia]], [[Indonesia]], [[East Timor]], and further afield such as [[India]] and [[Sri Lanka]].<ref name=\"LaiTan2010\">{{cite book|editor1=Walton Look Lai|editor2=Chee Beng Tan|title=The Chinese in Latin America and the Caribbean|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=xrGShVU6VrgC&pg=PA12|accessdate=8 January 2016|year=2010|publisher=BRILL|isbn=90-04-18213-6}}</ref>{{rp|12}}<ref name=\"Herrera-Sobek2012\">{{cite book|editor=Mar\u00eda Herrera-Sobek|title=Celebrating Latino Folklore: An Encyclopedia of Cultural Traditions|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=bDIwZ8BieWcC&pg=PA59|accessdate=8 January 2016|volume=1|year=2012|publisher=ABC-CLIO|isbn=978-0-313-34339-1|page=59}}</ref><ref name=\"Binder1993\">{{cite book|editor=Wolfgang Binder|title=Slavery in the Americas|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=M25cDaIsFNYC&pg=PA100|accessdate=8 January 2016|volume=4|year=1993|publisher=K\u00f6nigshausen & Neumann|isbn=978-3-88479-713-6|page=100}}</ref><ref name=\"Meagher2008\">{{cite book|author=Arnold J. Meagher|title=The Coolie Trade: The Traffic in Chinese Laborers to Latin America 1847-1874|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=H7dBmBsd-XgC&pg=PA194|accessdate=8 January 2016|year=2008|publisher=Arnold J Meagher|isbn=978-1-4363-0943-1|page=194}}</ref> Filipinos made up most of their population.<ref name=\"Russell2009\">{{cite book|author=James W. Russell|title=Class and Race Formation in North America|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=PZgR6ubuUXcC&pg=PA27|accessdate=8 January 2016|year=2009|publisher=University of Toronto Press|isbn=978-0-8020-9678-4|page=27}}</ref> The people in this community of diverse Asians in [[Mexico]] were called \"los indios chinos\" by the Spanish.<ref>{{cite journal|format=PDF|url=http://148.202.18.157/sitios/publicacionesite/pperiod/Lhistoricas/pdfs/vol1/4.pdf|title=El alcalde de los chinos en la provincia de Colima durante el siglo xvii: un sistema de representaci\u00f3n en torno a un oficio|trans-title=The mayor of the Chinese in the province of Colima during the seventeenth century: a system of representation surrounding trade|language=es|journal=Letras Hist\u00f3ricas|first=Claudia Paulina|last=Machuca Ch\u00e1vez|date=Autumn\u2013Winter 2009|issue=1|publisher=Ciesas Occidente|pages=95\u2013116|url-status=dead|archiveurl= https://web.archive.org/web/20140407081131/http://148.202.18.157/sitios/publicacionesite/pperiod/Lhistoricas/pdfs/vol1/4.pdf|archivedate=7 April 2014|df=dmy}}</ref> Most of these workers were male and were obtained from Portuguese traders, who obtained them from [[Portuguese Empire|Portuguese colonial possessions]] and outposts of the [[Estado da India]], which included parts of India, [[Bengal]], [[Malacca]], Indonesia, [[Nagasaki]] in Japan, and [[Macau]].<ref>{{cite journal|format=PDF|first=D\u00e9borah|last=Oropeza Keresey|url=http://www.redalyc.org/pdf/600/60022589001.pdf|title=La Esclavitud Asi\u00e1tica en El Virreinato de La Nueva Espa\u00f1a, 1565-1673|trans-title=Asian Slavery in the Viceroyalty of New Spain, 1565-1673|language=es|journal=Historia Mexicana|volume=LXI|date=July{{ndash}}September 2011|accessdate=31 August 2017|issue=1|publisher=El Colegio de M\u00e9xico|issn=0185-0172|pages=20\u201321}}</ref><ref>{{cite journal|format=PDF|first=D\u00e9borah|last=Oropeza|url=http://www.mexicanistas.eu/uploads/Ideas%20centrales%20en%20torno%20a%20la%20esclavitud%20asiatica%20en%20la%20Nueva%20Espana,%20Deborah%20Oropeza.pdf|title=Ideas centrales en torno a la esclavitud asi\u00e1tica en la Nueva Espa\u00f1a|trans-title=Central ideas surrounding Asian slavery in New Spain|language=es|journal=Historia Mexicana|date=Fall{{ndash}}Winter 2009|issue=1|publisher=Encuentro de Mexicanistas 2010 (La esclavitud asi\u00e1tica en el virreinato de la Nueva Espa\u00f1a, 1565-1673)|page=2|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140407092442/http://www.mexicanistas.eu/uploads/Ideas%20centrales%20en%20torno%20a%20la%20esclavitud%20asiatica%20en%20la%20Nueva%20Espana%2C%20Deborah%20Oropeza.pdf|archivedate=7 April 2014}}</ref> [[Chinese people in Spain|Spain received some of these coolies]] from Mexico, where owning a ''Chino'' coolie showed high status.<ref name=\"LaiTan2010\"/>{{rp|13}} Records of three Japanese coolies dating from the 16th century, named Gaspar Fernandes, Miguel and Ventura who ended up in Mexico showed that they were purchased by Portuguese slave traders in Japan, brought to Manila from where they were shipped to Mexico by their owner Perez.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://news.asiaone.com/News/AsiaOne+News/Asia/Story/A1Story20130514-422430.html|title=Japanese slaves taken to Mexico in 16th century|work=[[Yomiuri Shimbun]]|via=Asiaone News|date=14 May 2013|accessdate=8 January 2016|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20161022120120/http://news.asiaone.com/News/AsiaOne+News/Asia/Story/A1Story20130514-422430.html|archivedate=22 October 2016}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|first=Ida|last=Torres|url=http://japandailypress.com/records-show-japanese-slaves-crossed-the-pacific-to-mexico-in-16th-century-1428777/|title=Records show Japanese slaves crossed the Pacific to Mexico in 16th century|newspaper=Japan Daily Press|date=14 May 2013|accessdate=8 January 2016|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160131111645/http://japandailypress.com/records-show-japanese-slaves-crossed-the-pacific-to-mexico-in-16th-century-1428777/|archivedate=31 January 2016}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|author=Preston Phro|title=To Mexico in Chains: The Tale of Three 16th Century Japanese Slaves|url=http://en.rocketnews24.com/2013/05/15/to-mexico-in-chains-the-tale-of-three-16th-century-japanese-slaves/|newspaper=Rocket News 24|date=15 May 2013|accessdate=8 January 2016}}</ref> Some of these Asian slaves were also brought to [[Lima]] in [[Peru]], where it was recorded that in 1613 there was a small community of Asians, consisting of Chinese, Japanese, Filipinos, Malays, Cambodians and others.<ref name=\"Bethell1984\">{{cite book|editor=Leslie Bethell|title=The Cambridge History of Latin America|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=hhNfVshMw64C&pg=PA21|accessdate=8 January 2016|series=Colonial Latin America|volume=II|year=1984|publisher=Cambridge University Press|isbn=978-0-521-24516-6|page=21}}</ref><ref name=\"L\u00f3pez-Calvo2013\">{{cite book|author=Ignacio L\u00f3pez-Calvo|title=The Affinity of the Eye: Writing Nikkei in Peru|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=mMY4-ffumwUC&pg=PA134|accessdate=8 January 2016|year=2013|publisher=University of Arizona Press|isbn=978-0-8165-9987-5|page=134}}</ref><ref name=\"Hoerder2002\">{{cite book|author=Dirk Hoerder|title=Cultures in Contact: World Migrations in the Second Millennium|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=1PDVdU4YZWgC&pg=PA200|accessdate=8 January 2016|year=2002|publisher=Duke University Press|isbn=0-8223-8407-8|page=200}}</ref><ref name=\"Cauti2005\">{{cite book|author=Fernando Iwasaki Cauti|title=Extremo Oriente y el Per\u00fa en el siglo XVI|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=tPwCeavlP9QC&pg=PA293|accessdate=8 January 2016|year=2005|publisher=Fondo Editorial PUCP|isbn=978-9972-42-671-1|page=293}}</ref>\n\nChinese [[Immigration|immigrants]], who in the 19th century took a four-month trip from Macau (then a Portuguese territory), settled as [[Employment|contract labor]]ers or coolies. Other Chinese coolies from [[Guangdong]] followed.\n80,000<ref name=smithbodies>{{cite web |last1=Katz |first1=Brigit |title=Remains of 19th-Century Chinese Laborers Found at a Pyramid in Peru |url=https://web.archive.org/web/20191111084210/https://www.smithsonianmag.com/smart-news/remains-19th-century-chinese-laborers-found-pyramid-peru-180964647/ |website=Smithsonian.com}}</ref> to 100,000<ref name=brownsla>{{cite web |last1=Hwang |first1=Justina |title=Chinese in Peru in the 19th century |url=https://web.archive.org/web/20191111084324/https://library.brown.edu/create/modernlatinamerica/chapters/chapter-6-the-andes/moments-in-andean-history/chinese-peru/ |website=Brown University}}</ref><ref name=smithbodies/> Chinese contract laborers, 95% of which were Cantonese and almost all of which were male, were sent mostly to the [[sugar]] plantations from 1849 to 1874, during the termination of [[slavery]]. They were to provide continuous labor for the coastal [[guano]] mines and especially for the coastal plantations where they became a major labor force (contributing greatly to the Peruvian [[Guano Era|guano boom]]) until the end of the century. While the coolies were believed to be reduced to virtual slaves, they also represented a historical transition from slave to free labor. A third group of Chinese workers was contracted for the construction of the railway from Lima to [[La Oroya]] and [[Huancayo]]. Chinese migrants were barred from using cemeteries reserved for Roman Catholics, and were instead buried at pre-Incan burial sites.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://phys.org/news/2017-08-peru-pre-incan-site-tomb-chinese.html |quote=The Chinese were discriminated against even in death, having to be buried in the pre-Incan sites after being barred from cemeteries reserved for Roman Catholics. |title=Peru discovers in pre-Incan site tomb of 16 Chinese migrants |date=August 24, 2017 |publisher=[[Phys.org]]}}</ref> Between 1849 and 1874 half<ref name=brownsla/><ref name=smithbodies/> the Chinese population of Peru perished due to abuse, exhaustion, and suicide<ref name=brownsla/> caused by forced labor.<ref name=brownsla/><ref name=smithbodies/>\n\n[[File:CDO Cienguilla.jpg|thumb|250px|left| Chinese school in Peru]]\n[[File:Chinatown, Lima20060002.JPG|thumb|250px|left| Chinatown in Lima]]\n[[File:Danza del le\u00f3n cdo.jpg|thumb|250px|left| Chinese Community in Peru - Dance of the Lion]]\nThere were almost no women among the nearly entirely male Chinese coolie population that migrated to Peru and Cuba.<ref name=\"LaiTan2010\"/>{{rp|143}}<ref name=\"McKeown2001\">{{cite book|author=Adam McKeown|author-link=Adam McKeown|title=Chinese Migrant Networks and Cultural Change: Peru, Chicago, and Hawaii 1900-1936|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=vix_3doZkH0C&pg=PA47|accessdate=8 January 2016|year=2001|publisher=University of Chicago Press|isbn=978-0-226-56025-0|page=47}}</ref> Peruvian women were married to these Chinese male migrants.<ref>{{cite book|page=[https://archive.org/details/orientalsasianam0000leer/page/75 75]|pages=|year=1999|accessdate=May 17, 2014|publisher=Temple University Press|volume=|author=Robert G. Lee|location=|title=Orientals: Asian Americans in Popular Culture|url=https://archive.org/details/orientalsasianam0000leer|url-access=registration|quote=chinese peruvian women.|isbn=1439905711}}</ref><ref name=\"Tan2004\">{{cite book|author=Chee-Beng Tan|title=Chinese Overseas: Comparative Cultural Issues|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=Ca7UAQAAQBAJ&pg=PA47|accessdate=8 January 2016|year=2004|publisher=Hong Kong University Press|isbn=978-962-209-661-5|page=47}}</ref><ref name=\"LeeLim\">{{cite book|author1=Josephine D. Lee|author2=Imogene L. Lim|author3=Yuko Matsukawa|title=Re/collecting Early Asian America: Essays in Cultural History|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=fjeAaEqo-CEC&pg=PA181|publisher=Temple University Press|isbn=978-1-4399-0120-5|pages=181\u2013}}</ref><ref name=\"Lai1998\">{{cite book|author=Walton Look Lai|title=The Chinese in the West Indies, 1806-1995: A Documentary History|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=fMrit6tcO_AC&pg=PA8|accessdate=8 January 2016|year=1998|publisher=University of the West Indies Press|isbn=978-976-640-021-7|page=8}}</ref><ref name=\"Gonzales2014\">{{cite book|author=Michael J. Gonzales|title=Plantation Agriculture and Social Control in Northern Peru, 1875\u20131933|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=oKt0BQAAQBAJ&pg=PT139|accessdate=8 January 2016|year=2014|publisher=University of Texas Press|isbn=978-1-4773-0602-4|page=139}}</ref> [[Africa]]n women particularly had mostly no intercourse with Chinese men during their labor as coolies, while Chinese had contact with Peruvian women in cities; there they formed relationships and sired mixed babies. These women originated from Andean and coastal areas and did not originally come from the cities; in the haciendas on the coast in rural areas, native young women of ''ind\u00edgenas'' (\"native\") and ''serranas'' (\"mountain\") origin from the [[Andes]] mountains would come down to work. These Andean native women were favored over Africans as marital partners by Chinese men, with matchmakers arranging for communal marriages of Chinese men to young ''ind\u00edgenas'' and ''serranas''.<ref>{{cite book|page=144|pages=|year=2010|accessdate=May 17, 2014|publisher=BRILL|volume=|author=Isabelle Lausent-Herrera|editor1=Walton Look Lai|editor2=Chee Beng Tan|quote=|location=|title=The Chinese in Latin America and the Caribbean|series=Brill ebook titles|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=xrGShVU6VrgC&pg=PA144#v=onepage&q&f=false|isbn=9004182136}}</ref> There was a racist reaction by Peruvians to the marriages of Peruvian women and Chinese men.<ref>{{cite book|page=145|pages=|year=2010|accessdate=May 17, 2014|publisher=BRILL|volume=|author=Isabelle Lausent-Herrera|editor1=Walton Look Lai|editor2=Chee Beng Tan|quote=|location=|title=The Chinese in Latin America and the Caribbean|series=Brill ebook titles|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=xrGShVU6VrgC&pg=PA145#v=onepage&q&f=false|isbn=9004182136}}</ref> When native Peruvian women (''cholas et natives'', ''Indias'', ''ind\u00edgenas'') and Chinese men had mixed children, the children were called ''injerto''; once these ''injertos'' emerged, Chinese men sought out girls of ''injerta'' origin as marriage partners. Children born to black mothers were not called ''injertos''.<ref>{{cite book|page=146|pages=|year=2010|accessdate=May 17, 2014|publisher=BRILL|volume=|author=Isabelle Lausent-Herrera|editor1=Walton Look Lai|editor2=Chee Beng Tan|quote=|location=|title=The Chinese in Latin America and the Caribbean|series=Brill ebook titles|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=xrGShVU6VrgC&pg=PA146#v=onepage&q&f=false|isbn=9004182136}}</ref> Peruvians of low class established sexual unions or marriages with the Chinese men, and some black and Indian women \"bred\" with the Chinese according to Alfredo Sachett\u00ed, who claimed the mixing was causing the Chinese to suffer from \"progressive degeneration\". In Casa Grande, highland Indian women and Chinese men participated in communal \"mass marriages\" with each other, arranged when highland women were brought by a Chinese matchmaker after receiving a down payment.<ref>{{cite book|page=|pages=|year=2014|accessdate=May 17, 2014|publisher=University of Texas Press|volume=|author=Michael J. Gonzales|quote=|location=|title=Plantation Agriculture and Social Control in Northern Peru, 1875\u20131933|series=|url=https://books.google.com/?id=oKt0BQAAQBAJ&pg=PT139&dq=chinese+peru+women#v=onepage&q=chinese%20peru%20women&f=false|isbn=1477306021}}</ref><ref>{{cite book|page=100|pages=|year=1985|accessdate=May 17, 2014|publisher=University of Texas Press|issue=Issue 62 of Latin American Monographs, No 62, Issue 62 of Institute of Latin American Studies|volume=Volume 62 of Texas Pan American Series|author=Michael J. Gonzales|quote=|location=|title=Plantation Agriculture and Social Control in Northern Peru, 1875-1933|series=Brill ebook titles|url=https://books.google.com/?id=I6-zAAAAIAAJ&q=when+recruits+arrived+placed+room+grooms+lined+up+opposite+highland+women+faces+each+directly+opposite+woman+contractor+claps+hand+signal+turn+around+man+wife+permits&dq=when+recruits+arrived+placed+room+grooms+lined+up+opposite+highland+women+faces+each+directly+opposite+woman+contractor+claps+hand+signal+turn+around+man+wife+permits|isbn=029276491X}}</ref>\n\nIn Peru and [[Cuba]], some Indian (Native American), [[mulatto]], black, and white women engaged in carnal relations or marriages with Chinese men, with marriages of mulatto, black, and white woman being reported by the Cuba Commission Report. In Peru, it was reported by ''[[The New York Times]]'' that [[Women in Peru|Peruvian black and Indian (Native) women]] married Chinese men to their own advantage and to the disadvantage of the men since they dominated and \"subjugated\" the Chinese men despite the fact that the labor contract was annulled by the marriage, reversing the roles in marriage with the Peruvian woman holding marital power, ruling the family and making the Chinese men slavish, docile, \"servile\", \"submissive\" and \"feminine\" and commanding them around, reporting that \"Now and then...he [the Chinese man] becomes enamored of the charms of some sombre-hued chola (Native Indian and mestiza woman) or samba (mixed black woman), and is converted and joins the Church, so that may enter the bonds of wedlock with the dusky se\u00f1orita.\"<ref name=\"Young2014\">{{cite book|author=Elliott Young|title=Alien Nation: Chinese Migration in the Americas from the Coolie Era Through World War II|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=ch8VBQAAQBAJ&pg=PA82|accessdate=8 January 2016|series=David J. Weber Series in the New Borderlands History|volume=4: Wiley Blackwell Concise History of the Modern World|year=2014|publisher=UNC Press Books|isbn=978-1-4696-1296-6|page=82}}</ref> Chinese men were sought out as husbands and considered a \"catch\" by the \"dusky damsels\" (Peruvian women) because they were viewed as a \"model husband, hard-working, affectionate, faithful and obedient\" and \"handy to have in the house\", the Peruvian women became the \"better half\" instead of the \"weaker vessel\" and would command their Chinese husbands \"around in fine style\" instead of treating them equally, while the labor contract of the Chinese coolie would be nullified by the marriage, the Peruvian wife viewed the nullification merely as the previous \"master\" handing over authority over the Chinese man to her as she became his \"mistress\", keeping him in \"servitude\" to her, speedily ending any complaints and suppositions by the Chinese men that they would have any power in the marriage.<ref>{{cite web|format=PDF|title=The Coolie Trade: The slavery of the present - The traffic of Peru - Hiring of the Coolie - Horrors of the middle passage the Coolie's fate|url=https://www.nytimes.com/1873/07/19/archives/the-coolie-trade-the-slavery-of-the-present-the-traffic-of-peru.html|date=28 June 1873|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150701053253/http://query.nytimes.com/mem/archive-free/pdf?res=9B0DE2D61539EF34BC4152DFB1668388669FDE|newspaper=New York Times|accessdate=17 May 2014|archivedate=1 July 2015}}</ref>\n\nAlthough Chinese Peruvians were well-integrated to Peruvian society, it did not come with an easy beginning. During the [[War of the Pacific]], Chinese labors led an uprising in support to Chile against Peru. Peruvians held Chinese as responsible to the Chilean invading army, and this led to the first ever [[Sinophobia]] in Latin America. Chinese were targeted and murdered by native Peruvians and it was not until 1890s that anti-Chinese [[pogroms]] stopped.<ref name=\"Taylor\">Taylor, Lewis. Indigenous Peasant Rebellions in Peru during the 1880s</ref><ref name=\"bonilla\">Bonilla, Heraclio. 1978. The National and Colonial Problem in Peru. ''[[Past & Present (journal)|Past and Present]]''</ref> Despite this, Chinese were barred from immigrating to the country until 1970s.<ref>[https://books.google.com/books?id=OP-EBAAAQBAJ&pg=PA87&lpg=PA87&dq=sinophobia+peru&source=bl&ots=hJsiEwA8Xe&sig=LVE_M83bDe-Mm2igEeTSldf_O4I&hl=en&sa=X&ved=0ahUKEwj4_L72g-vaAhWJurwKHb1ZBrIQ6AEIMDAB#v=onepage&q=sinophobia%20peru&f=false/ Dragons in the Land of the Condor: Writing Tus\u00e1n in Peru]</ref>\n\nAnother group of Chinese settlers came after the founding of [[Sun Yat-sen]]'s republic in 1912, and another after the establishment of [[Communist Party of China|Communist rule]] in 1949.\n\nIn 1957, Cantonese speakers constituted 85 per cent of the total Chinese immigrant population, the rest of whom were Hakka speakers.<ref>{{cite book|title=Ch\u02bbiao|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=XdocAQAAMAAJ|volume=3, Issue 2|year=1974|publisher=Basement Workshop, Incorporated|page=35|chapter=The Chinese in Peru|quote=\"...but in 1957 speakers of Cantonese constituted 85 per cent of the total, the rest of whom were Hakka speakers.\"}}</ref>\n\n{{Culture of Peru}}\n\n===Modern-day immigration===\nRecent Chinese immigrants settled in Peru from [[Hong Kong]] and Macau in 1997 and 1999, owing to fear of those territories returning to Communist rule, while others have come from other places in [[mainland China]], [[Taiwan]], and southeast Asian Chinese communities, including those of Malaysia, Indonesia, [[Singapore]] and the Philippines. Many [[Chinese Indonesian]]s came to Peru after anti-Chinese [[May 1998 riots of Indonesia|riot]]s and [[massacre]]s in those countries in the 1960s, 1970s, and late 1990s. These recent Chinese immigrants make Peru currently the home of the largest ethnically Chinese community in [[Latin America]].\n\n===Emigration===\nMany Chinese Peruvians left Peru in the 1960s and 1970s. Most of them headed to the [[United States]], where they were called [[Chinese American]]s or Peruvian Americans of Chinese descent, while others went to [[Canada]], [[Spain]], mainland China, Hong Kong, Macau, Taiwan, [[Australia]], or [[New Zealand]].{{Citation needed|date=December 2011}}\n\n===Role in the economy===\nAfter their contracts ended, many of them adopted the last name of their patrons (one of the reasons that many Chinese Peruvians carry Spanish last names). Some freed coolies (and later immigrants) established many small businesses. These included ''chifas'' (Chinese-Peruvian restaurants - the word is derived from Chinese term, {{linktext|lang=zh-Hant|\u5403\u98ef}} ({{zh|j=ci<sup>3</sup>faan<sup>6</sup> |p=ch\u012bf\u00e0n}}) which means \"to eat rice or to have a meal\"). Calle Cap\u00f3n, [[Chinatown, Lima|Lima's Chinatown]], also known as Barrio Chino de Lima, became one of the [[Western Hemisphere]]'s earliest Chinatowns. The Chinese coolies married Peruvian women, and many Chinese Peruvians today are of mixed Chinese, Spanish, African or [[Indigenous peoples of the Americas|Native American]] descent. Chinese Peruvians also assisted in the building of railroad and development of the [[Amazon Rainforest]], where they tapped rubber trees, washed gold, cultivated rice, and traded with the natives. They even became the largest foreign colony in the Amazon capital of [[Iquitos]] by the end of the century.\n\n==Notable people==\nThe vast majority of Chinese descendants in Peru do not carry a Chinese surname, since their ancestors, when they arrived in Peru, were baptized or adopted the surnames of their patrons, Catholic saints or some very common Castilian surname. \n\n=== Politics & business ===\n{|\n|\n* Ephraim Wong Lu <small> (businessman) </small>\n* Enrique Wong <small> (congressman) </small>\n* Erasmus Wong Lu <small> (businessman) </small>\n* Erick Chuy <small> (businessman, accountant, missionary) </small>\n* Eugenio Chang Cruz <small> (lawyer, professor and senator) </small>\n*Felipe Tam Fox <small> (administrator, official and former head of the SBS) </small>\n*[[Humberto Lay Sun]] <small> (congressman) </small>\n*Isabel Wong-Vargas <small> (businesswoman) </small>\n*Jes\u00fas Wu <small> (businessman) </small>\n*[[Jos\u00e9 Antonio Chang]] <small> (industrial and political engineer) </small>\n|\n*Juan Pablo Chang Navarro <small> (politician) </small>\n*Julio Ch\u00e1vez Chiong <small> (mayor) </small>\n* Julio Ch\u00fa M\u00e9riz <small> (politician) </small>\n* Luis Chang Reyes <small> (engineer and politician) </small>\n* Magdalena Ch\u00fa <small> (Statistical expert and former head of the  [[National Office of Electoral Processes|ONPE]]) </small>\n* Nelson Chui Mej\u00eda <small> (former president of the Lima Region) </small>\n*Rolando Martel Chang <small> (Superior Judge of Lima and professor) </small>\n* Rosario L\u00f3pez Wong <small> (Superior Criminal Prosecutor of Lima) </small>\n*Rub\u00e9n Chang Gamarra <small> (lawyer and politician) </small>\n|}\n\n=== Entertainment ===\n{|\n|\n* A\u00edda Tam Fox <small> (poet and historian of Peruvian cuisine) </small>\n* Alberto Ku King <small> (journalist) </small>\n* Annie Yep <small> (TV host, journalist, and model) </small>\n* Anthony Choy <small> (lawyer and investigative journalist ufologist) </small>\n* Antonio Wong Rengifo <small> (film director) </small>\n* Sui Yun (Katty Wong) <small> (poet) </small>\n* Jonatan Relayze Chiang <small> (filmmaker) </small>\n* Julio Villanueva Chang <small> (journalist)</small>\n|\n* Mar\u00eda In\u00e9s Ching <small> (journalist) </small>\n* Miguel Yi Carrillo <small> (journalist) </small>\n* Milly Ahon Olgu\u00edn <small> (cultural historian) </small>\n*M\u00f3nica Chang <small> (journalist) </small>\n*[[Patty Wong]] <small> (model and TV presenter) </small>\n* Pedro Mo <small> (rapper) </small>\n*Ra\u00fal Chang Ruiz <small> (journalist, director of the Oriental Magazine) </small>\n|}\n\n=== Athletics ===\n{|\n|\n* Augusto Yep <small> (footballer) </small>\n* [[Edwin V\u00e1squez Cam]] <small> (Olympic champion in shooting, [[London 1948 Olympics | London 1948]]) </small>\n* [[Freddy Wong]] <small> (skater) </small>\n* H\u00e9ctor Cruz Cheng <small> (soccer player) </small>\n*Iv\u00e1n Miranda Chang <small> (tennis player) </small>\n*Jorge Koochoi Sarmiento <small> (footballer, 8 times national champion) </small>\n|\n* Juan Chang Zevallos <small> (footballer and journalist) </small>\n*Julio Lores Col\u00e1n <small> (footballer) </small>\n*[[Katherine Miranda Chang]] <small> (tennis player) </small>\n*Luis Pau Le\u00f3n <small> (footballer) </small>\n*Mariano Loo Granda <small> (footballer) </small>\n*Patty K\u00fa Flores <small> (tennis player) </small>\n|}\n\n=== Culture ===\n{|\n|\n* Alejandro Chu <small> (archaeologist) </small>\n* Apu-Rimak <small> (plastic artist) </small>\n* Carolina Chang Tam <small> (keyboard player) </small>\n* Celia Wu Brading <small> (historian and translator) </small>\n* Chez Wong <small> (cook) </small>\n* Emilio Choy Ma <small> (social scientist) </small>\n* Javier Wong <small> (chef) </small>\n|\n* [[Juan Wong Paredes]] <small> (musician) </small>\n* Juan Wong Popolizio <small> (musician) </small>\n* Julio Mau <small> (singer) </small>\n*Mao Wong L\u00f3pez <small> (musician) </small>\n*Marcelo Wong <small> (plastic artist) </small>\n*Rosa Fung Pineda <small> (archaeologist) </small>\n|}\n\n=== Other ===\n{|\n|\n*Alejandro Chung Hern\u00e1ndez <small> (teacher) </small>\n* Alicia Garcia Yi <small> (teacher, CCPCH director) </small>)\n* Eugenio Chang-Rodr\u00edguez <small> (linguist and professor) </small>\n* Jorge C\u00e9liz Kuong <small> (general) </small>\n* Jos\u00e9 Gallardo Ku <small> (economist) </small>\n|\n*Olga Lock Sing <small> (chemical and scientific engineer) </small>\n* \u00d3scar Tang Cruz <small> (physicist and professor) </small>\n*[[Pedro Zulen]] <small> (philosopher and librarian) </small>\n* Ra\u00fal Chau Quispe <small> (Auxiliary Bishop of Lima) </small>\n* Johnny Ching Paravecino <small> (Teacher-Researcher) </small>\n|}\n\n==See also==\n{{Portal|Peru|China}}\n*[[Asian Latin Americans]]\n*[[Chinatown, Lima]]\n*[[Chinatowns in Latin America]]\n*[[History of Peru]]\n*[[Japanese Peruvians]]\n*[[Overseas Chinese]]\n\n==References==\n{{reflist|colwidth=30em}}\n\n==Further reading==\n*{{citation|last=De Trazegnies Granda|first=Fernando|title=En el pa\u00eds de las colinas de arena: reflexiones sobre la inmigraci\u00f3n china en el Per\u00fa del S. XIX desde la perspectiva del derecho|publication-place=Lima|publisher=Pontificia Universidad Cat\u00f3lica del Per\u00fa|year=1994|isbn=978-84-89309-82-1|oclc=31349975}}\n**Translated into Chinese as {{citation|author=\u7af9\u78a7 [Zhu Bi]|author2=\u814a\u6885 [La Mei] |language=zh-Hans |script-title=zh:\u6c99\u56fd\u4e4b\u68a6\uff1a\u5951\u7ea6\u534e\u5de5\u5728\u79d8\u9c81\u7684\u547d\u8fd0 |publisher=\u4e16\u754c\u77e5\u8bc6\u51fa\u7248\u793e [World Affairs Press]|year